A Republican strategy to oppose Obama's reelection
The Republican leadership justifies its policies with the need to combat electoral fraud.
However, the Brennan Center considers the latter a myth, affirming that voter fraud is less common in the United States than the number of people killed by lightning.
Republican lawyers have only recorded 300 cases of voter fraud in the United States in the last 10 years.
One thing is certain: these new rules will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, these measures are partly undermining the democratic system of the United States.
Unlike Canada, the US states are responsible for conducting elections in each state.
In this regard, most American governments have since 2009 enacted new laws that make it more difficult to register or vote.
This phenomenon gained importance after the November 2010 elections, in which 675 new Republican representatives were registered in 26 states.
As a result, 180 bills were introduced in 2011 alone that restrict the exercise of the right to vote in 41 states.
The new election laws require voters to present a photo ID and proof of U.S. citizenship.
In addition, these laws also shorten the time limits for early voting, invalidate the right to register as a voter on election day and deny citizens the right to vote, for which there is a judicial record.
Before the 2006 election, no state in the United States required voters to show a photo ID.
Indiana was the first state to make such a demand.
The Supreme Court of the United States upheld the constitutionality of the Indiana law in 2008.
The Republican authorities hastened to extend this practice to other states.
Over the past two years, they've been promoting bills in 34 states that require voters to show a photo ID.
It is important to note that, unlike Quebec, US citizens do not have a universal ID card such as the Health Insurance Card.
In fact, 11 percent of U.S. citizens, or 21 million eligible voters, do not have a photo ID issued by a government agency in their state.
In addition, five million new voters in 2012 do not have such a card.
However, it is often more than a hundred dollars to obtain the required ID.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities and low-income people.
In fact, 25% of African Americans, 15% of those with incomes under $35,000, 18% of citizens over 65 and 20% of voters between 18 and 29 do not have the required photo ID.
This goes further.
Students who are considered voters and who are more likely to vote for democratic candidates are not allowed in several states to use their photo ID issued by their institution.
On the other hand, the same states allow members of fishing or hunting clubs who vote more for the Republican side to use the cards issued by those clubs for elections.
Before 2004, no state required proof of citizenship to vote.
Arizona was the first state to make such a requirement.
Since 2011, a dozen states have passed laws requiring voters to prove their U.S. citizenship.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting the Hispanic vote.
Because it's obvious that two out of three Hispanic voters prefer the Democratic Party.
In addition, in 2011, Republican lawmakers in eight states passed legislation that eliminated voter registration on Election Day.
You have also restricted the right of individuals and groups to assist voters who wish to register.
These restrictions are not without consequences.
For example, the voter registration campaigns in the 2004 general elections helped register some 10 million citizens.
The measures adopted since 2009 have reduced the share of new voter registration in 2010 by 17% compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican lawmakers in five other states have passed legislation aimed at shortening the time period for early voting.
For example, in the 2008 general election in Florida, 33% of the voters who voted in advance were African-American, even though they make up only 13% of the state's voters.
The same is true of the Hispanic population.
The latter accounted for only 11% of the electorate, but 24% of the citizens who voted in advance.
In contrast, whites, who made up 76% of the electorate, made up only 46% of those who voted in advance.
Of course, democratic lawmakers and their supporters have vigorously opposed the passage of laws that restrict voter registration.
Several bills have been blocked by vetoes by Democratic governors.
The attorney general of the United States has intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
They were able to partially limit the damage.
For example, only 16 of the 34 states have passed laws requiring the presentation of a photo ID.
However, the new rules introduced in 2012 will undoubtedly make it more difficult to exercise the right to vote.
Democratic critics denounce the partisan nature of the laws passed and see them as a clear goal to influence the results in the states that will determine 2012.
A 2011 report by the Brennan Center shows that those states that passed these laws accounted for 171 of the 270 electoral votes needed to win the presidency.
It is too early to confirm with certainty that these changes to the electoral legislation will have a significant impact on the outcome of the 2012 presidential election.
But one thing is certain: these new rules will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, these measures are partly undermining the democratic system of the United States.
Early detection of prostate cancer: should the test be done or not?
The PSA test does indeed sometimes give erroneous results, with false negatives or false positives leading to unnecessary medical intervention.
This leads to greater reluctance among already undecided men to undergo early detection tests.
Should the test be done or not?
We've got two specialists.
In the US studies, there were numerous interferences between control groups, making it difficult to interpret these data and make clear recommendations.
Another study, this time from Europe, concluded that there was a difference in mortality between patients with and without early detection.
This study also showed that, on follow-up after 12 years, the likelihood of metastasis is 30 to 40% higher if no early detection is performed.
That's why I recommend testing at age 50 or 40, if you have a direct relative who already has prostate cancer.
Men of African-American descent are also at a higher risk.
The most important thing is to make the right decision as soon as cancer is diagnosed.
There are cancers that are aggressive and others that are indolent.
The patient must be made to really understand the extent of the risk of his cancer by showing him the possible options for not treating prostate cancer if it does not affect his quality of life in the long term, and in these cases, he is more likely to opt for active monitoring of the disease.
Today, many men who are diagnosed with cancer are not treated because their cancer is not aggressive and is not life-threatening.
They are suggested to be actively monitored and treated if the disease progresses.
The criteria for deciding who should be treated and who should not are being determined with increasing precision.
That's why I still recommend that you run the test.
Most important, though, is to talk to your doctor about whether it should be done.
Movember has developed a tool in collaboration with the International Society of Urology to evaluate the advantages and disadvantages of the PSA test.
This document (currently only in English, but a translation will be available shortly) can be downloaded from: http://ca.movember.com/fr/mens-health/prostate-cancer-screening
Prevention of the disease
Unfortunately, there is no miracle cure for cancer.
Despite advances in research, adopting a healthy lifestyle remains the best way to reduce the risk of developing it.
It is estimated that 30 percent of cancers could be prevented if everyone ate well and exercised enough.
"If there were no smokers, this number would rise to at least 50 percent", says André Beaulieu, spokesman for the Canadian Cancer Society.
However, it is estimated that about 10 percent of cancers are hereditary.
Several are still completely unsolved.
The Canadian Cancer Society continues to make the fight against tobacco addiction a priority, despite the decline in the number of smokers.
Smoking is responsible for 85% of lung cancer cases.
It's also a risk factor for several other cancers.
It is very damaging to people's health.
"Today there are still 1.5 million smokers in Quebec", said spokesman André Beaulieu.
Encouraging data: 10 years after quitting smoking, the risk of dying of cancer is cut in half.
The weight
According to the Canadian Cancer Society, overweight and obesity also contribute to the disease's onset.
They seem to increase the risk of breast, colon, rectal, esophageal, pancreatic and uterine cancer.
"Research shows that regular physical activity throughout life protects against colorectal cancer", he adds.
The diet
The organization also recommends limiting red meat consumption.
In too large a quantity, it increases the risk of developing colon and rectal cancer.
Sausages should also be avoided.
The preservation of meat by smoking, drying or salting may lead to the formation of carcinogens.
"The latter can damage the body's cells and lead to cancer", he explains.
Other
In recent years, several scientists have investigated the link between vitamin supplements and cancer.
But their findings are not conclusive at this time.
According to the Canadian Cancer Society, the studies on vitamin E are contradictory.
While one study found a decrease in the risk of prostate cancer, another showed an increase.
The effect of vitamin D on cancer has also not been clearly demonstrated.
Mr Beaulieu also stresses the importance of discussing his concerns and family history with his doctor.
"The early detection test does not lead to cancer".
The Higgs boson is being analyzed.
The announcement of the probable discovery of the Higgs boson caused quite a stir last summer, and for good reason.
In fact, it's believed that this boson is involved in nothing less than the mechanism that is responsible for the mass of all objects in the universe.
And finally, it's the last particle that the Standard Model predicted would exist -- our best or least-false explanation of the nature and behavior of matter -- but has not yet been observed empirically.
But for physicists, it's not yet entirely certain that this is really the Higgs.
We know without a shadow of a doubt that we have a real new particle, and that it is very similar to the Higgs boson predicted by the Standard Model.
Furthermore, this seems to be confirmed by new data presented this week at a major physics congress in Kyoto, but there is still no data to be absolutely sure.
But let's assume that it's actually the Higgs, because there seems to be a small risk of being wrong, and let's look at what it is.
There is a law in this world that is inevitable and inevitable, which means that two objects cannot be in the same place at the same time.
It is not possible to break this rule - and don't try too hard, because you will get hurt.
Because even if particle physics is a really strange world, it turns out that it also has a law like this: the Pauli exclusion principle, which says that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state", where that "state" is largely made up of some of their properties.
Based on this, physicists divide particles into two categories.
In one corner are the good citizens, known as fermions, who politely obey the Pauli principle.
And in the other one, the bosons are moving, a vicious gang of anarchists who have nothing sacred -- certainly not this principle, which means they can actually be in the same place at the same time.
These bosons, according to the Berkeley Laboratories website The Particle Adventure, which is absolutely amazing, are divided into two groups: the mesons, which we won't discuss here, and the "force particles" that are the way the great forces of nature are spread and that the Higgs boson is somehow related to.
But it's important to note here that these bosons aren't all as exotic creatures as you might think.
If you are able to read this chronicle, it is only because of a boson of extraordinary banality: the photon, or "particle of light", which is the "messenger" of the electromagnetic force.
That is, when a particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, the electromagnetic field is "disrupted" at that very spot, much like a pebble thrown into a pond.
This "interference" creates an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.), and this wave is nothing more than a photon and thus one of the bosons "carriers of the force".
More stable field
The same thing applies to the Higgs boson, with the difference that another field, the Higgs field, has to be "disrupted" for this boson to show up.
However, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field; the agent must reach very high energies, somewhat comparable to a frozen pond whose surface could only be cut by a very large rock.
So a giant particle accelerator like CERN - the Large Hadron Collider is a ring with a circumference of 27 kilometers! - is needed to achieve such energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again helpful in explaining the relationship between the Higgs and mass.
It is not all particles and not all materials that interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do this, but others don't - for example, a sheet of paper would never stick on the refrigerator by itself.
And equally, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that do have mass, while the others (like the photon, by the way) have no mass.
What good can all this research be, asks Mrs Plamondon?
For science, they are used to verify the Standard Model (SM), and they also allow physicists to study accurately any discrepancies between the observations and predictions of the SM.
There are, by the way, many physicists who are desperate to find such discrepancies, since the slightest difference could open a door to a "new physics" and fill some holes in the model.
It must be said that the latter has still major flaws, as it does not offer an explanation for gravity (ups!) and dark matter, which makes up about 80% of the matter in the universe (again ups!).
However, no such deviations have been found at CERN so far.
Effects
The impact of this research on the general population is more difficult to predict, but it would be a mistake to assume that there is none.
By the way, in the early '60s, the pioneers of the laser at Bell Labs had no idea that their work would spark such a revolution.
They saw scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, the late physicist Willard Boyle - who worked at Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in the 1960s, and who even developed the first continuous-flow laser in 1962 - told us that the laser was initially seen as more of a "laboratory toy".
Can you imagine?
In addition, applications can also arise from all the instruments surrounding research.
For example, in 1969, Willard Boyle, while working in optics, developed a small light sensor.
Although not its original purpose, this sensor now serves as the "eye" of all digital cameras worldwide, and it won him the Nobel Prize in Physics in 2009.
Of course, this doesn't mean that the activities of the LHC will necessarily change our lives, but it does mean that you really never know...
Palliative care is the best way to die...
With its committee on "Dying with Dignity", Quebec recently discussed the sensitive issue of the end of life.
The debate must resume soon, although a draft law is being prepared.
However, much remains to be done in this important area.
Le Devoir has tried to look at this more closely.
A few weeks ago, Mr L. was living alone in his apartment in Montérégie.
The prostate cancer that was eating him up had given him two years to live.
"They gave me five years to live, I managed seven", he said halfheartedly, lying in his bed at the Victor-Gadbois hospice in Beloeil, where he had arrived the day before.
"But it's always a shock, you can't be prepared for it", he says.
The disease is doing its job: an immeasurable weakness prevents him from going to the toilet alone and even eating by himself.
Sitting at the table at a delicious lunch, he resignedly agrees to help with the meal.
He even manages to smile and talk to strangers who are busy around him, bring him his medicine, and offer him a bath.
The courage of ordinary death.
"My greatest wish is that my diarrhea be cured, because it is humiliating", he says.
A few hours later, the team found a cure for this disease.
"We all experience standing up to pee", says Pierre Brodeur, a psychologist at the Victor-Gadbois home.
Returning to the childhood phase is an unacceptable humiliation for some people.
"It depends on the person's ability to take a step back", he says.
Because according to several people who work in palliative care, big events are happening in the midst of these setbacks.
The patients who are admitted to the Victor-Gadbois hospice are all suffering from cancer.
They have a maximum life expectancy of three months.
At this stage, they are no longer overwhelmed by the so-called "healing" care of the doctors and nurses who care for them.
For 89-year-old A., the worst fear is "knowingly and suffocatingly".
But through the illness, I really got to know my kids.
"I have good children", she adds.
"I have no more desires in life", she says before accepting a mask to help her breathe.
She is still expecting a last visit from her son, who is coming from Italy.
The Victor-Gadbois Home is a group of volunteers who provide care and assistance with food intake.
Palliative care is used when there are no other options.
To make dying more pleasant.
In Quebec, there is one palliative care bed for every 11,700 inhabitants.
That's a small price to pay when you consider that we're all going to die one day.
Here, life continues under the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors at the home.
Both on the level of physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
The dying person is given a mouthwash with brandy or Pepsi, depending on his wishes.
Diabetics no longer have to control their blood sugar.
And death is part of life.
Last night we served Mr. X a beer, and he died during the night.
This morning, his son will drink the beer at the feet of the deceased.
"We help family members and patients alike", says Nathalie Savard, director of nursing.
At the Victor-Gadbois home, every day is different.
Next to a 93-year-old man enjoying the last family gathering in the yard, well supported by his pillow as a toast is to his honor, a 36-year-old man, surrounded by his parents, wife and two young children, dies tragically after trying everything to survive.
"For six months now, three to five beds have been filled with cancer patients under 45", says Dr. Christiane Martel, worried.
53% of the patients admitted to Victor-Gadbois' home come from their home, 47% come from the hospital.
Problems of access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, which is care designed to alleviate the suffering of patients when they reach the end of their lives, whether at home, in a hospital or in a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as the Victor-Gadbois Home and the Palliative Care Society in the Greater Montreal area, specialize more or less exclusively in caring for cancer patients.
It is precisely this serious inadequacy in Quebec's health care system that has caused several palliative care doctors to be apprehensive about the passage of a law regulating assisted dying and assisted suicide.
Since October, a manifesto has been circulating, signed by prominent figures in palliative care such as Dr Balfour Mount and Dr Bernard Lapointe, to express their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, the Quebec health system is not capable of ensuring that everyone has the right to quality palliative care before accepting assisted dying.
Recently, she says, I saw a patient who was in the emergency room for 14 days with severe pain and no relief was given.
I'm afraid the only reason patients want to die is because they don't get proper health care.
And at the same time, several oncologists are treating their patients with the utmost persistence until the last day, despite the worst prognosis.
Hélène Richard's chances of survival were already minimal when she stopped a cumbersome course of chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was going to stop the treatment, she said that she regretted giving up the fight, she told me.
But she told me I was finished!
No omnipotent care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who have asked to die thank the nursing staff for not granting their wish after their pain is alleviated by a palliative care team.
It must be made clear, however, that palliative care is not omnipotent in the treatment of pain.
According to Elsie Monereau, head of palliative care at the Society of Home Palliative Care in Greater Montreal, 8% of patients do not respond to pain treatment.
Thus, at the end of life, doctors often resort to terminal sedation, which involves putting the patient to sleep either sporadically or permanently until the time of death.
We can no longer pretend not to see this side of suffering.
Patients without pain relief will increasingly have the option of resorting to this terminal sedation.
Patients whose pain is not relieved all say the same sentence: "I want to die".
But that doesn't necessarily mean, "I want you to put me to sleep", but "I want my pain relieved".
