Large-scale property scandal in Quebec
Every day, officials from the road office, construction companies, political party fundraisers and specialists in the Italian mafia tell what they know about a grand "system" involving the construction industry, officials, politicians, trade unionists and mafiosi.
An industry that was very expensive for the Quebec taxpayer, especially in the 1990s and 2000s.
"It's strange how the system is falling apart since drastic measures were taken", jokes Jacques Duchesneau, a Quebec MP and former Montreal police chief.
The scandal was exposed by him as a result of an in-depth investigation into the embezzlement of contracts for road construction in Quebec, which the then Prime Minister had only reluctantly agreed to.
The Duchesneau report established a direct link between industry, secret party financing and bribing of officials.
"Since the inquiry began in 2010", he points out, "the Department of Transportation alone would have saved a billion dollars in contracts" because some people were using their instincts to get their share!
The Charbonneau Commission "has already brought down two mayors", he adds, hoping to "discover the tactics behind the individuals".
A permanent anti-corruption unit set up in 2011
The permanent anti-corruption unit, established in 2011, is also making great efforts with its troops of government auditors, investigators and analysts.
And the police of the "Marteau troop", which since 2009 has made the Montreal "sewage cartel" more restrained in the artificial inflation of contracts...
In recent weeks, she has carried out a series of house searches and made accusations of fraud and corruption against municipal officials such as Frank Tampino and Richard Marcotte, the mayor of a suburb.
Next on the list would be Gilles Vaillancourt, who has just resigned as mayor of Laval, Quebec's third-largest city.
He is suspected of having repeatedly accepted bribes in exchange for public contracts.
The specific charges against the engineers of the Montreal Road Building Authority, as well as Italian entrepreneurs, such as Tony Accurso and Lino Zambito, were specifically mentioned.
The latter has made a splash by explaining to the Commission how the 'system' for obtaining public contracts works.
He himself paid 3% of the value of contracts he won in Montreal for several years to a mafia-linked intermediary who transferred the money to the Union Montreal, the party of Mayor Gérald Tremblay.
Mr Zambito has been involved throughout the 2000s, giving more than C$88,000 to provincial parties, mainly the Liberals who were in power at the time.
He also admitted to organising illegal fundraising for former Liberal Vice-President Nathalie Normandeau.
Plumbing contracts for which he artificially inflated the cost
In Montreal, the "system" of corruption worked smoothly.
Former civil engineer Gilles Surprenant described this in detail to the Commission: over a period of ten years he received gifts, invitations to travel, golf tournaments, restaurants and ice hockey games, and bribes of $736,000 from the construction company in exchange for plumbing contracts, the cost of which he artificially inflated.
Other officials in the road office admitted that they had been defrauded by artificially inflating the bills for false benefits by 30-40%.
In addition, a promoter of the mayor's party, Martin Dumont, accused Mr Tremblay of deliberately ignoring a shadow budget that filled his coffers with black money.
As a result of these revelations, Mr Tremblay resigned in early November, plunging Montreal into a serious crisis.
Chantal Rouleau was one of the first Montreal deputies to sound the alarm.
As mayor of Rivière-des-Prairies, in the east of the island, she fought back in 2010 against the sale of a municipal property that was bought for $5 million and sold for $1.6 million to developers in the booming real estate market.
70% black money in election campaigns
She says that the investigation that is finally conducted "pulls a thread that allows us to understand the workings of the system that ants have undermined in order to stop the evil and expose the culprits".
She says the procedure is "painful but positive".
We are in the process of cleaning up the wound, but we need a Montreal-only investigation unit and a monitoring unit to prevent a return to questionable practices.
How to clean.
I'm going to be regular.
Jacques Duchesneau, for his part, notes that "officials have stolen several hundred million dollars", but is especially concerned about the role of "officials who know about the tactics" if they were not involved in the fraud!
Based on a 70% black money contribution to Quebec's campaign financing, he jokes: "I was told that this was just a faint blur of reality".
The Quebec government proposes to limit donations to political parties to $100, which he says will not change the situation: "Until campaign spending is strictly limited, black money will be in the political arena".
He recommends a complete overhaul of the system of public procurement and party funding: "We cannot fall any lower; by courageously getting to the bottom of things, we can rebuild the house on a more solid foundation with more controls and legislation".
If this story damages the international reputation of Quebec and Montreal, Mr. Duchesneau urges those who laugh at it to look in their own backyard...
