Bitcoin allows you to pay and sell without a bank
The opposite of current monetary exchange based on central banks, identified transactions and processing fees between the parties involved.
Moreover, as so often happens, these technologies have a political vision: the belief that the current monetary system, shaped by banking monopolies, leads to financial crises.
In fact, the Bitcoin invented by Satoshi Nakamoto (a pseudonym) is both a virtual currency (but convertible into dollars, euros, etc.) and a secure exchange protocol like BitTorrent, which allows direct file exchange.
With 15,000 computers on the network, about 200,000 transactions have already been recorded.
A few thousand websites accept Bitcoin as a donation or payment.
After reaching a high of $30 in June 2011, Bitcoin fell to $2 five months later before recovering to around $10 today (the prices are listed on the website bitcoincharts.com).
Nothing particularly impressive compared to world trade in real currencies or financial products.
Nevertheless, the European Central Bank (ECB) has shown interest in this in a report on virtual currencies published in October.
It describes Bitcoin as "the most successful virtual currency", "competing with the dollar or euro" and "similar to traditional currencies".
Bitcoin is different from other types of virtual currencies such as "credits" used to advance in a video game, which can be won or bought (and sometimes exchanged) by playing.
The social network Facebook has also developed a similar system.
However, the trade is always controlled and handled by a central authority.
With Bitcoin, all nodes are simultaneously account holders, auditors, money issuers, and buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Every transaction between two users is actually between two e-mail addresses in the form of an e-mail.
The difference is that the user can choose a different address for each payment, which ensures anonymity.
A number of the data related to this transaction shall be electronically signed by a double-encryption system.
This allows the network to verify the authenticity of the transaction.
The contents of the file also make it possible to ensure that the bitcoins traded are in the public account book, which is distributed throughout the network.
The crucial step is to enter this new transaction into this ledger.
