It is a fragmentation of the file, i.e. the conversion of a large file into a shorter and more distinct electronic fingerprint.
The computers "take" the new transaction and add a number to it before the whole thing gets "hacked".
The aim is to find the number that gives a particular fingerprint (many zeros at the beginning).
Once that number is found, the other nodes can easily check if it is the correct one.
The transaction is thus permanently linked to the chain of all other transactions, and any modification would change the fingerprint.
If a user tries to pay twice very quickly (less than 10 minutes) with the same money for fraud, only one of the two transactions would be validated by the network and the other would remain unlinked because both have different fingerprints.
The computer that solves the problem gets 50 bitcoins.
