Each year, 13 million foreign workers come to Moscow, St. Petersburg, and other cities in Russia.
Most of them are citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to earn money to support their families back home.
On December 1, a law came into force that requires every migrant worker to pass a test that certifies knowledge of the Russian language.
The scheme is currently only available to migrants who wish to work in the service sector, the municipal housing sector and the retail trade.
However, in time, the Federal Migration Agency says that the tests will become mandatory for all guest workers.
It is not only a question of language tests, but also of Russian history and the foundations of legislation.
Language skills must be demonstrated for both obtaining and renewing a work permit.
Exceptions apply only to citizens of countries where Russian is the official language.
The law also exempts persons who obtained their diplomas and certificates before the collapse of the USSR in 1991.
The meaning, problems and protection of rights
The examination centres will be under the aegis of the Pushkin Institute of the Russian Language, the Russian University of International Friendship, Moscow State University, St. Petersburg State University and other Russian universities.
The migrants can take the tests in all cities, and more than 160 centres have already been opened in Russia.
The initiative to introduce the tests was supported by the deputies of the State Duma and the Federal Migration Agency.
Civil rights activists, on the other hand, asked the following question in the press several times before the law came into force: What is the point of this?
What changes does the requirement to have a language proficiency bring for both Russians and foreign workers?
The main aim, according to Migration Agency spokesmen, is to reduce the number of forced labourers.
"Many people are talking about protecting the rights of migrant workers", says Viktor Sebelev, head of the Federal Migration Agency's representation in Tajikistan.
However, their rights must be protected before they leave.
Only organized recruitment will solve 90% of the problems of foreign workers.
Migrants without jobs, education, language skills and medical examination face problems.
Sebelev is convinced that a future migrant without language skills will inevitably encounter people with bad intentions who, under the pretext of helping, will put him in a dark, cramped barracks, where he will endure with dozens of his peers for months without food and documents, working 12 to 14 hours a day.
We get a lot of complaints from our migrants.
"At home you are promised one thing, and when you arrive you are cheated, your passports are taken away and you do not get the promised salary", confirms Tolib Shwaripov, head of the Tajik Migration Agency's main labour migration department.
Don't you swear, boss!
Yet many citizens of Central Asian republics who want to earn money in Russia admit that they not only do not speak the language of the country of destination but also can hardly express themselves in writing in their own language.
Of course, this is not so much their fault as the evil: few Turkmen, Uzbeks and Tajiks can afford even a reasonable basic education.
Because their families do not even have the money to feed their children, let alone to buy decent clothes, shoes, and school supplies.
As teenagers, these children then immediately seize the first opportunity to make money.
"It's difficult without language skills", they admit.
"You feel humiliated and inferior".
Civil rights experts emphasize the following important aspect of the law.
Only legal immigrants are required to take the test.
If you do not have this status, you will not take the exam and therefore not get an official job.
Meanwhile, most of the migrant workers continue to stay in Russia illegally.
"Welcome" or "No unauthorized access"
Many migrants confirm that it is not easy to obtain official status in Russia.
The reason is bureaucratic hurdles and, of course, language difficulties.
In addition, legalization costs money: 12 to 16 thousand rubles.
A fake registration can be made quickly and for only one and a half thousand.
The Russian police know that our documents are mostly fake and we are not registered, and this leads to cases of blackmail.
"They want one or two hundred rubles for cigarettes and tea", Umed Khushkadamov, a Tajik, told reporters.
"Just don't be afraid of the cost of false papers"
