Šimon Ornest: We want to gather positive energy at our concerts
What do you think about the world ending in less than a month?
This is one of those disaster stories that we humans like to jump on.
And with our band, The Tap Tap, we're kind of making fun of it, saying that we're the only band in the world that can harness enough positive energy to stop or prevent the end of the world.
In December, you will also be performing a unique project with three concerts against the end of the world.
Can you introduce the project to our readers?
This is a nationwide fundraiser we've been planning for two years.
To do this, we want to use the marketing potential of the Mayan calendar, which is predicted to end on December 21 at 11:10 a.m.
The day before, on 20 December, three concerts will take place simultaneously in Prague, Brno and Ostrava, starting at 21:00.
The end of the concerts is said to be around the time the Mayan calendar ends on the Pacific island of Kiribati, which is 12 hours ahead of us in the time zone.
Who's idea is that?
I thought I was the one who first came up with the idea, and then we worked with our graphic designer Honza Augusta to design it.
We want to not only gather enough positive energy to prevent the end of the world, but we also want to think with the public about the state in which we will leave this world to our children.
To mark the end of the Mayan calendar, we have also developed a unique collection of anti-doomsday shoes, T-shirts, bags and key chains, which can be purchased from www.e-tap.cz to help us.
The Tap Tap also recorded the so-called anti-doomsday anthem "Doomsday Fails" with other artists.
The anthem is already very popular on YouTube. Will it be played at the benefit concerts?
Of course, and at the very end, assuming everything works out and the end of the world doesn't happen...
The anthem is to be sung simultaneously by all the performers at all three concerts.
The national anthems will also be broadcast live on Czech television.
The lyrics of the anthem are by Tomáš Hanák, who also plays the main character of Jesus in the video, Xindl X also sings with...
How did you come to work with them?
We also cooperate with other personalities of the Czech cultural scene, which is connected with the fact that we realize many charity events and concerts...
We try to involve these people in our projects.
It turns out that most people are interested in working with us and enjoy it.
What purpose does the proceeds from the doomsday concerts serve?
For the establishment of the accessible education centre Studeo, which we have been working on for six years with the association Tap at the Jedlička Institute.
Students at the Jedlička Institute are regularly supervised by tutors who help them with various leisure activities.
Since the students themselves do not have the means to visit the editors, we would like to help them in this way.
As part of the completion of the Jedlička Institute, a separate building will be built, into which we will then move with this project.
At each concert, several groups and performers perform.
What criteria did you use to select these?
We wanted to put together a program that would appeal to all generations, including children.
In Prague, for example, Chinaski, Support Lesbians, Illustratosphere with Dan Bárta, The Tap Tap, Marián Bango and Jiří Suchý are performing.
You can find more information on the website www.kpks.cz.
Are similar "major events" planned for the future?
In May we will perform at the Prague Spring for the first time, and for this concert we will also prepare an interesting programme with interesting guests.
We would also like to play at the Czech House in New York next year, and I personally - if we are in the United States at that time - would also like to combine this with performances in Washington and Chicago.
Your plans for abroad are not small. You've already performed in Madrid, Brussels, London or Moscow.
The Tap Tap, however, is a group made up of people with disabilities.
How do you manage these trips logistically and organizationally?
It's not as bad as it looks at first glance.
Five of our members are wheelchair users, which means that the wheelchairs have to be carried in the luggage compartment.
Nevertheless, it has always worked without problems, ČSA and British Airways have always been very well prepared for us, so that I have sometimes wondered.
Even in Moscow, where we were recently, there were no problems.
Your travels abroad give you a comparison of how accessibility countries are, how disabled people are treated, etc.
How have you experienced these things so far?
After Madrid, Luxembourg, London and other cities where everything works better than here, we have just witnessed in Russia that everything is still in its infancy in the East.
Compared to Prague, Moscow is not handicapped-friendly at all.
It is not even self-evident that you let a wheelchair user in the elevator, for example.
Fortunately, there are also associations that try to draw attention to the problems of people with disabilities.
And in what way do we have to catch up with the more developed countries?
There's still a lot of things we're stuck with...
It should be noted, however, that improvement in the situation always depends on the efforts of those concerned.
In London and Madrid, it is quite common for people with severe disabilities to be able to move independently in public spaces, to go to museums, to use toilets, etc.
It is not very common for a large group of disabled people to be actively involved in social activities, and we are a little ahead of the West in this respect with the band The Tap Tap!
Respect in the public and accessibility is one thing, but only when great athletes, artists, actors, politicians or lawyers come from our ranks will things really start to change.
So far, these are only isolated cases of particularly strong-willed personalities.
Tap is very popular right now, but if we go back a few years, what motivated you to start a band in 1998?
I started as a tutor at the Jedlička Institute, where I met many young people who were interested in doing something intense.
And since I'm a musician myself and play saxophone, I founded a music company with a colleague.
Well, as our host, Láďa Angelovič, says, with time, things get out of hand.
But the band only became known in recent years, am I wrong?
It is true that working with well-known singers has helped us; besides, we have also started to actively promote ourselves.
We've come to realize that if you're doing something and you can't see it on the outside, then in a sense, your performance doesn't exist.
The EU funding also enables us to afford good editors, high-quality equipment and so on.
Was it your goal to get this far with The Tap Tap?
From the beginning, I felt the potential to do things differently.
In show business, people often copy each other.
This is logical in its own way, since anything new is considered with caution and accepted only after a long time.
There are few things that are truly unique, and I dare say that tap tap is one of them.
The first impression the spectator usually has is of course pity; that's only natural...
But this compassion is absolutely superfluous, because people with disabilities are not lonely and abandoned beings to be pitied.
They are people who can live a full life and develop if they have the necessary means.
I always say that when people with disabilities achieve something, it's not just progress for themselves, it's progress for the whole society.
Was it also helpful to this success that you are a strict boss, as you hear from many people?
If you want to do something well, you must not compromise in many things and you must also demand a certain amount of discipline.
I think this is quite normal.
Some come to us with romantic ideas, and when they realize that they have rehearsals twice a week, have to go through the preparatory phases and spend a lot of time on concert tours, then the enthusiasm for many quickly fades.
But that's how it works everywhere, in every band that's serious about working and trying to get something done.
The Tap Tap currently has twenty members.
How many of these were there from the beginning, i.e. since 1998?
There's only one, Lada Angelovic.
We're an open group, people come and go, you can't stop them.
Anyone who wants to be a part of this is always welcome.
