Poland and space.
Last week, Poland was admitted as the twentieth member of the European Space Agency (ESA) at a meeting of the Council of Ministers of the member countries, making it the second member country from the former Eastern bloc (after the Czech Republic, which joined ESA on 12 November 2008).
Poland began close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and participated in several ESA projects in the following years.
Poland's journey into space began much earlier.
Even before World War II, Polish space enthusiasts were engaged in space exploration, but they did not always find understanding.
I recall, for example, the lecture given by A. Šternfeld on 6 December 1933 at the Warsaw Observatory, in which the author presented ideas from his pioneering work "Introduction to Cosmonautics".
However, the ideas of the young engineer (born 1905) left the audience cold, and after years Šternfeld still remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski had shown interest in his work.
In 1934 Šternfeld won the Prix REP-Hirsch for "Introduction to Cosmonautics", which was donated by Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch.
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899-1966) later became an important advocate of astronomy and space travel.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish journals and wrote several books on these scientific disciplines.
Gadomskis' world-renowned contribution to space exploration was recognized in part by the naming of one of the craters on the far side of the moon after him.
As early as 1925, a railway drainage system was built in Poland, with a rocket engine planned for it.
The author of the draft and the details of this project remained unfortunately unknown.
It is not even clear whether the rocket should be used to launch or to slow down the Draisine.
The information on this comes exclusively from the contemporary press.
In 1933, the Polish infantry began to study rocket-propelled grenades.
The research was carried out by the Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia Institute in collaboration with Prof. Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Prof. Gustaw Mokrzyckiegi.
The documents provided show that the research had progressed to the stage of practical testing.
The research was interrupted by the German invasion.
In 1937, the design of a photoelectric fighter rocket by Ing. Rohoziński appeared in the professional press, and the following year the work "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" by the author Leliwa-Krzywoblocky appeared.
Both projects concerned the military use of the rocket propulsion system.
Shortly before the war, all projects for the military use of rocket technology were coordinated by the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy).
The Committee was set up in 1937, but after two years of activity, its work was terminated by the outbreak of war.
Further articles on space travel appeared in the Polish press after the war, thanks to the work of the Polish Space Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
The first mention of this society is in the November 1954 issue of the magazine Problemy, which contains four extensive articles on space travel.
The article by Prof. M. Subotowicz contains the proposal to establish a space society.
At that time, the first satellite projects were already underway, and it was clear that space exploration would have a future.
The Polish Space Society (PTA) was already seeking to join the International Space Federation (ISF) when it was founded in 1951.
The following year, the first PTA chairman, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902-1959), became Vice-Chairman of the International Federation for Space.
He held this office until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the PTA has been a major player in the development of the highly successful meteorological rocket (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), the first Polish rocket for scientific research.
The first type, the RM-1, was completed in 1957, and first launched on 10 October 1958.
The rocket, with a maximum altitude of 1,800 m, was about 80 cm long and weighed less than 5 kg.
Later an improved version, the RM-1A, was built, and in 1959 flight tests began in the Błędów Desert with the RM-2 two-stage rocket.
The missile was 1.4 meters long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
A further stage of development should already be capable of real scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should reach a flight altitude of up to 14.5 km and be used for observing high winds.
In 1962, however, further development was stopped.
The successor to the first RM-type rockets was the Meteor-1 rocket, developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was designed as a two-stage rocket, its total length was 510 cm and the launch weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types of this rocket were developed (Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C), which differed in the size of the space for carrying scientific instruments.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a carrying capacity of 0.4 litres, the Meteor-1B 0.34 litres and the Meteor-1C 0.62 litres.
The maximum altitude of all three types was 37 km.
In the years 1965 to 1968 the Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Institute of Aviation, the first flight tests of which began in October 1970.
Meteor-2 had a takeoff weight of 380 kg and was capable of carrying a payload of 10 kg to an altitude of approximately 60 km.
The Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built afterwards.
It is also worth noting that Poland joined the Committee for Space Research (COSPAR) in 1960, followed two years later by the establishment of a national COSPAR committee.
Poland also participated in space exploration with Soviet satellites as part of the Intercosmos program, and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second Intercosmonaut after the Czech Vladimír Remek.
