The CIA, in cooperation with Canadian authorities, managed to get the refugees out of Iran, helping them with an extravagant story to conceal their true identity - they were traveling on Canadian passports disguised as members of a film crew who were supposedly visiting the country for a science fiction film shoot.
Combination of genres
The plan, developed by exfiltration expert Tony Mendez, also required the cooperation of Hollywood.
To make the cover story credible, articles about this film project were published in trade magazines, press conferences were held, and the fictitious production company had a real office.
The details of this operation were kept secret for a long time, and the film is based on the memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck's film is a special combination of several film genres.
On the one hand, it is a realistic political thriller, but at the same time it is also a so-called "caper movie", i.e. the story of a successful hussar play such as the film Ocean's Eleven.
This changes the mood levels in the film - on the one hand, the documentary scenes from Tehran (the title sequence shows iconic contemporary photographs, and there are no major differences in the filming of the same situations).
On the other hand, there are the loose passages from Hollywood, which are ironic and slightly over-the-top.
And then there's the scenes from CIA headquarters and other institutions-- men in suits at the conference table, in the hallways, on the phone...
Ben Affleck has made a remarkable career comeback with this film.
A derided actor has become a respected director, and even as an actor he is no longer the target of ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature film after the crime drama Gone Baby Gone (2007) and the thriller City Without Mercy (2010).
It is also Affleck's first film not set in his hometown of Boston.
The sense of the atmosphere of the place was one of the characteristics that set the director's previous films apart from the standard Hollywood.
Affleck, however, also demonstrates this sentiment in Argo, where Tehran is "played" by Canada.
The best scenes of the film are set in the streets and show the reconstruction of events that really happened - the opening sequence of the storming of the message is very impressive in its clarity, yet conveys the sense of confusion and unpredictability that occurs when the story moves somewhere.
Affleck and his team have a similar effect on fictional scenes (the fake film stick on a bazaar in Tehran).
Too much action in too many places
The director also had to deal with the fact that the story doesn't actually have many cinematically exciting scenes.
He works with the little one, but he is quite successful, sometimes adding to the reality - which is not always so elegant (the scenes of the impending crisis at Tehran airport being deflected by a phone call in America, or the chase on the runway, seem a bit artificial).
Argo's weakness is its overly wide dispersion, caused by the need to show too much action in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman are very charming in their roles as Hollywood employees, but their characters deserve more space, and they are far from alone in the film.
It's a movie that you can watch with some interest, and you can enjoy the design and retro style that's reminiscent of a 1970s thriller.
But it is difficult to get enthusiasm.
But it is sufficient as a reminder of a piece of history that is still alive and proving how overblown the ideas of the all-powerful and all-knowing intelligence services are.
Guidelines for the inflation of balloons, bananas and circuses
The server www.bankovnipoplatky.com, which annually publishes a survey on the most absurd bank charges, decided to hold the "Most Absurd Regulation or Idea from the EU Workshop" competition this year.
"We came up with this idea with the recent EU plan to introduce a 40% female management ratio in large European companies", said Patrik Nacher, who organises the survey, to the Právo newspaper.
The Commission has already made a number of proposals to this effect, and I am sure that the Commission will be able to do so.
Until then, women had an advantage in life insurance because they represented objectively less risk to insurance companies.
"More incredible ideas from the EU workshop can be nominated by the end of this year.
The actual vote will then take place by the end of February 2013", Nacher said.
The EU's controversial regulations include the mandatory addition of bioethanol to fuels, which is harmful to the environment, the ban on reliable mercury thermometers, simply because they contain a relatively small amount of this dangerous substance, and the chicken cage size directive, which has made eggs significantly more expensive this year.
The actual ban on the use of the term 'buttercoating' or the ban on the sale of conventional light bulbs have also been criticised in the past.
Bananas must be 14 cm long
The EU apparatus often decides under pressure from this or that trade and industry lobby, whose demands are usually represented in Brussels by one or more Member States (the Czech Republic, for example, is currently trying to veto the demands of Czech banks).
Lobbying interests also pushed for bananas of the highest commercial grade in the EU to be at least 14 cm long and not have a 'curvature anomaly'.
The European Commission defended itself by arguing that it was merely harmonizing the disparate national standards that would hinder trade.
The EU has already softened the standards for fruit and vegetables, despite opposition from some countries, saying that the previous directives would lead to food waste.
One possible candidate for victory in this survey is last year's EU regulation, which requires balloons to be sold with a warning that children under eight cannot inflate the balloon without adult supervision.
The EU cited an American study which found that balloons are the leading cause of child death by suffocation.
A similar restriction already applies to children up to 14 years of age when using market straws.
Weird ideas at home
A directive that applies to European officials themselves is also relatively absurd - anyone who holds an official position in the EU is not allowed to use the name Macedonia because of the sensitivity of the subject for Greece and must say FYROM (Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia) instead.
The server Bankovnípoplatky.com, in cooperation with the Association of Liberal Economists Laissez Faire, nominated the EU regulation on the size of food stocks in the territory of a member state, in addition to the so-called absurdities.
The EU thus set the maximum amount of food stocks that could be on the territory of the Czech Republic on the day of our accession.
The Czech Republic, for example, exceeded the volume of preserved mushrooms, for which we were subject to a heavy fine.
The survey organisers were also impressed by the idea that certain countries should be paid for not having a sea or by the idea of giving grants for grant applications.
These ideas did not come from Brussels, of course, but from Prague.
"We are at a disadvantage because we have no sea.
We will apply to the EU for reimbursement", said Jaroslav Palas (ČSSD), then Minister of Agriculture.
It argued that the cereal harvest was very high and that the state stores were overcrowded as a result of the so-called intervention purchases.
The Czech Republic has another way to ports, so the EU should pay us hundreds of millions of euros, according to Palas.
The European Commission finally went so far as to invite the Czech Republic to tender for the purchase of cereals from countries without access to the sea.
The Ministry of Regional Development, headed by Minister Pavel Němec (US-DEU), offered grants for grant applications to municipalities, specifically to be used for grant applications to Brussels.
EU: Bizarre regulations are the exception
While regulations are easily the target of criticism in the Member States, some experts say that the EU's efforts to regulate and thus to make the European Union more effective and evolving deserve more recognition.
A more serious problem, according to these experts, is EU funding for projects that have nothing to do with deepening European integration but have been forced on the budget negotiations of individual Member States.
The Czech Republic is also feeling the emotion of having to fight in Brussels, like other Member States, for the right to use specific names for traditional products, and not always winning.
Although the Czech Republic was able to defend the name "Olomoucké tvarůžky" after a six-year battle with Germany and Austria, the domestic rum (Tuzemský rum), whose tradition goes back to the 19th century, our producers had to rename it "Tuzemák".
The name 'rum' may only be used for products of sugar cane distillate, not for products of sugar beet.
The official list of products registered in the EU now includes the world-famous Feta and Gorgonzola, the Lubeck marzipan and Parma ham, Karlsbad zwieback, carp from Pohořelice and Třeboň, and Saazer hops.
The EU trade mark is used to promote Pardubice gingerbread or Hořic rolls.
