MVRDV architects prove that true adventures are not just in the head - on the example of Spijkenisse and the recently built Bücherberg - 2 photos
"I find the building funny, it looks futuristic, and it's finally something interesting to see", says Lisette Verhaig, a passerby on the side of the road.
And Stefan Spermon, an IT technician at a large company nearby, says, "Yes, it's nice, the house".
But I wonder why we need a library today.
Everyone has Internet, iPad and e-books.
No one volunteers to go to one of those old-fashioned libraries anymore, do they?
Spijkenisse, a sleepy town on the outskirts of Rotterdam, is a strange record holder.
The municipality of 80,000 inhabitants has the lowest education rate in the whole of the Netherlands.
To counteract this stupidity, a few years ago it was decided to contribute to public education by recreating the seven fictitious bridges depicted on the euro banknotes as beautifully painted steel-concrete miniatures.
The success of the education offensive was limited.
And so the city fathers realized that there was only one way to master statistics: a library!
Winy Maas of the Rotterdam architectural firm MVRDV, master of daring bar diagrams and producer of funny, often cynical buildings, took the matter with the usual serenity and appeared at the competition hearing in 2003 with five books under his arm and a smile on his face.
And while the jury was still looking around in perplexity and shrugging, the naughty Maas piled his fine, great-sized gift up to a pyramid and ended his action-packed speech with the words: "Dear City Council!"
So that's it, my proposal for the Book Mountain of Spijkenisse, the so-called Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the 30 million euro mountain is being filled in.
It is part of a revitalization project that also includes a underground garage, a supermarket, a post office and a few adjacent residential and row houses with a total of 50 apartments.
In early November the Bücherberg was awarded the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012".
The project is also nominated for the Dutch National Wood Award 2012.
This makes the faceless small-town town, which until now had nothing more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian zone and an astonishingly ugly city hall, behind whose white facades one would be inclined to suspect a dairy factory, richer for a piece of contemporary architecture.
But most importantly, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in its history.
The Long Way to the Book
First impression: the book eldorado under the cheese bell.
Although there is an elevator that leads through the middle of the mountain range, the true joys of space and reading are unlocked by the pedestrian climb of the topography.
The interior, which is glazed all around, is bright and clear, the burnt-out clinker floors and the elegant street lamps speak unmistakably the language of a public city square.
The urban ambience is perfect.
They're already looking for park benches, dogs and boys and girls playing football.
And books everywhere, books, books.
"Usually the bookshelves are along the facade, and in the middle is a large, dark room, which is usually uncomfortable and impersonal", says Winy Maas.
We've turned the classic room configuration upside down and molded the reading area from the inside out.
The interior of the bookshelf is used skillfully: in the middle are offices, Internet library, chess club, environmental center and home technology center.
A special pleasure is the black bookshelves, which are sometimes wall coverings, sometimes sillings, sometimes staircases.
The look, the feel and the smell are foreign.
Even experienced architects and civil engineers shake their heads at the unknown building material.
"We wanted to work with recycled materials here", explains Joop Trouborst, project manager at the Municipality of Spijkenisse, when asked by the Standard.
And so one day we came across a suitable agricultural waste product on a farm in Friesland.
For many years, a millimeter-thin plastic film has been used in greenhouses and fields in the Netherlands as a root support.
It's cheap and time-saving.
The thin fabric lasts for a season or two, then it's ready for the lockdown.
For the library, the fibers were pressed into four-centimeter-thick plates - the first ever in such quantities.
Under heat and pressure, the so-called agricultural plastic (APP) turns a dark, homogeneous, load-bearing material that smells like a new car and sports shoes.
105 steps to the top.
At the end of the nearly 500-meter trek, the literature café offers not only a fantastic view of the city but also Dutch croquettes and ficus trees.
They provide atmosphere, but most importantly, they provide the right humidity in the literature mountain.
Donating for the New Soul
"You wouldn't believe it, but despite the glass, this house is an ecological model", says Trouborst.
Heated and cooled by geothermal energy.
Although the Bücherberg is under a glass collapse, the sun shines only briefly inside even on sunny days.
The wide wooden glue bars that line the glass facade provide shade and absorb much of the sun's radiation.
The indoor climate is very pleasant.
The rest will be done by fully automatic rollers.
Stefan Spermon, the initial IT skeptic, had already ventured into the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was there too.
And so is TCM teacher Cynthia Bogarde, who even calls the Boekenberg the "long overdue soul" of Spijkenisse.
The reason: At the opening a few weeks ago, each resident was invited to donate a book from his personal collection.
The aim is to fill the gaps in the library, which is still not fully stocked - currently 70,000 items.
The concept has taken off.
The shelves are full to the brim.
"Nothing is worse than a half-empty library", says architect Winy Maas.
"I think that, thanks to our invitation, every resident now has a certain relationship with this new house.
Everyone knows his book is part of this building.
And if it's just for decoration.
The new system of social security is a new one.
Spijkenisse has written literary history.
Young and uneducated as she may be.
This is finally a starting point for identity.
Szabo: "Germans must play a greater role"
Germany abstained in the vote on the inclusion of Palestine.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on US-European relations, Berlin balances this on a narrow diplomatic level.
Deutsche Welle: Earlier this week, Germany initially signaled that it would vote against the Palestinians' request for observer status at the United Nations.
But then Berlin refrained.
Why? Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support what the Israelis did in Gaza.
Now, however, Germany must be careful because of its special relationship with Israel.
But at the same time, I don't think it supports the American position.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence - without, however, being too critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained from voting on the establishment of a no-fly zone.
This was eventually enforced by NATO.
Does Germany find it difficult to take a clear position on important international issues?
Yes, that's right.
This is because it is changing its foreign policy from one that was managed by the United States, so to speak, to one that is German.
The European Union is not a coherent and unified policy.
So the Germans are meeting between the fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they are still learning their role, but they are on the way to a more 'normal' foreign policy.
A foreign policy like France or Britain.
What does a 'normal' foreign policy mean in concrete terms from the German point of view?
It shows a willingness to take positions which are independent of those of the USA or European partners when it comes to national interests.
I believe that German foreign policy is motivated by economic policy, that is, by exports and its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany's economic interests are to a certain extent different from those of the other great powers and therefore Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced the attitude to the Middle East conflict and the vote at the UN?
On the one hand, Germany has large markets in the Middle East, particularly in the Gulf States.
So we have to be careful not to embarrass the public, but also the elites, in the Arab countries.
It certainly does.
But I wouldn't want to give it too much weight either, because it's not a completely one-sided relationship.
But it certainly plays an important role in German thinking.
Has Germany damaged its relations with the United States by abstaining from important decisions, such as the vote on Palestine?
I believe that there is a great deal of understanding in Europe and even in the United States of America for the German position.
I therefore do not think that this was a break as dramatic as the one in Libya.
Perhaps Germany will even gain some respect for itself.
It is a sign that it is being taken seriously as an international player and that its interests must be taken into account.
There are different opinions in Europe on the Palestinian initiative.
The United States, on the other hand, has been clear in its support for a veto.
Are there differences of opinion between the United States and many European nations?
Because of American domestic policy, these differences have always existed.
I think the Obama administration has a pretty good understanding of the European position.
But given the political situation here, the government cannot, of course, publicly represent this position.
I believe that the real differences of opinion are not as great as they always seem.
If you look at the relationship between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, Obama is not that enthusiastic about Netanyahu's policies.
Does Germany find it difficult to reconcile its close relations with Israel and the USA on the one hand and the position of the most important partners in the EU on the other?
I think that's what makes it so difficult for the Germans.
It would of course be a little easier for the Germans if there were a coherent and unified European policy, which is not the case at present.
So they can't be part of a broader line and instead have to push things from their own position.
That is what they are doing with the euro.
I believe that in the future Germany will take a leading role in pushing Europe to a European position.
This is not easy for Germany, of course, because of its relationship with Israel.
This has always been a sensitive subject.
But I think the Germans realize that they need to play a more independent role.
Does Germany see itself as an important international player - does Germany want to take on a leading role at all?
Or is Germany still struggling to take the lead?
Germany is not yet used to this, it is still unpleasant and, for obvious reasons, it is still difficult for the country to play a greater role.
If we look at the euro crisis, for example, every time Germany takes on a greater role, various anti-German sentiments are released.
That doesn't make it easy for the Germans.
That's the old problem, you don't want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
In this way, Germany is in a much more difficult position than the United States.
It has to be open to all kinds of neighbors and opinions, and that's not easy.
The US influence in European politics is continually declining, but the EU is not currently filling this vacuum.
The Germans will simply have to play a greater role.
Even if they don't like it, it's unpleasant and makes them even more unpopular - c'est la vie!
Stephen Szabo is Deputy Director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, an institute where academics and policy experts from Europe and North America collaborate to research the challenges facing the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he specializes in German politics, US foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
"Brand protection in China: When Puma and Armani suddenly become Chinese"
Armani is a world-famous brand, Polo Ralph Lauren is too.
But what is Armani Polo?
This is a name which is officially registered in China but which is not related to the companies of origin.
Yet it is protected as long as the actual namesake does not complain.
And even then, it's not clear if they'll be right.
"It's becoming increasingly difficult for foreigners to protect their trademarks in China", says Thomas Pattloch, a lawyer at Taylor Wessing, who specializes in infringements in the Far East.
Every week, a new case lands on my desk.
The imitators need only a few letters to register their trademarks.
So Gucci becomes Lu-Gucci, instead of Prada, you have Prada-Kny.
German companies are also being legally copied in this way, such as the sportswear manufacturer Puma.
Pattloch opens a folder with records from the Trademark Office in Beijing.
On 14 September 2010, a Chinese company registered the Zegna DF Puma trademark, a registered trademark also used by the Ermenegildo Zegna fashion house.
It is well known that the Chinese are world champions in copying and infringing intellectual property.
In the big cities, there are multi-storey department stores that sell almost exclusively counterfeits.
But Pattloch's case is different: on behalf of his clients, he is opposed to Chinese companies being officially granted by the Trademark Office the right to use a name already protected elsewhere.
The Chinese call it "Bang Mingpai", a passenger badge.
The word is based on "Bang Dakuan".
That's women chasing rich men.
The Chinese authorities are not guilty
"This is bad for business, we have to fight it", says Pattloch.
"The brand is diluted, the uniqueness is lost, the image damage is enormous".
The financial losses and legal costs for the industries concerned are in the millions, especially for expensive flagship products.
According to market research company CLSA, China is the third largest and fastest growing luxury goods market with a volume of EUR 15 billion per year.
However, the removal of dubious trademark entries is difficult and costly.
The procedure can take up to nine years, with uncertain outcome.
Pattloch reports cases in which the Court rejected claims because the name in question had become a "market reality" after a long period of time.
If the plaintiff is unlucky, he may even have to pay the plagiarist money for infringing his trademark in China, says Pattloch.
Sometimes the law of the jungle rules here.
Famous cases also involve graphic elements.
In 2009, Daimler lost a legal dispute with the construction machinery manufacturer Sany, the company that recently acquired the German concrete pump manufacturer Putzmeister.
The Chinese are therefore still allowed to use an emblem similar to the Mercedes star.
The Volvo buyer Geely originally used a blue and white logo reminiscent of BMW; the dispute was settled, Geely had to change it.
Fashion maker Lacoste lost in China to imitators from Hong Kong and Singapore who turned their eyes away from the famous crocodile.
The Chinese authorities are not guilty.
The CTMO in Beijing admits that there were shortages in 2010 due to insufficient staff and space.
The Commission has also been asked to provide a detailed description of the measures taken to combat the problem.
The number of unresolved objections fell by 22%.
Nearly 57,000 such cases were closed, a 75 percent increase over the previous year.
Nevertheless, 81,500 appeals are still pending in the Office.
The cost of addressing this is high
As so often in China, the numbers are impressive.
Last year, the CTMO received more than 1.4 million trade mark applications, almost a third more than in 2010.
This is a record and means that China has topped the list of new cases worldwide for the tenth time in a row, the agency said.
The same applies to the stock of all valid trade marks, totalling 5.5 million.
In 2011, fees amounted to 1,8 billion yuan.
Simply put, this means that each registration costs on average 1280 yuan or 160 euros.
The cost of addressing this is manifold, as the case of the German family business Freudenberg shows.
For more than seven years, the company has been fighting a Chinese plagiarist.
The German authorities were able to get the illegal manufacture of imitation car parts out of the way.
However, the imitator continued to secure the Chinese rights to the Freudenberg brand.
They themselves failed to do so because family names could not be protected in Germany, says Hanno Wentzler, the chairman of Freudenberg Chemical Specialities in Munich.
The CTMO also rejected the Munich objection.
In the next two cases Freudenberg was right, but the opponent continues to fight to this day.
You gotta be careful as hell .
Now the matter is pending before the Supreme Court.
Wentzler is confident that the case will be brought to a good conclusion and praises the professionalism of the courts.
But he also says: "The procedure is extremely time-consuming, costly, and nerve-wracking".
The internal costs were hard to quantify, and the company's archives even had to go through a hundred-year-old files to provide evidence.
Five years ago Freudenberg offered the other party a "high six-figure euro amount" to settle the case, but it was in vain.
"That shows how much it's worth to us", says Wentzler.
The dangers in the Far East threaten to spill back into Europe.
That is, when counterfeiters secure unprotected trademarks.
For example, a Chinese manufacturer in Germany wanted to register the name Freudenberg for footwear and leather.
The Group has long since abandoned this business area, but it was able to avoid registration.
"You have to be hell-bent", says Wentzler.
Both he and Pattloch advise German companies to be very careful when doing business with China.
Relying on international trademark rights is not enough, but foreigners should "register anything worth protecting in China", Wentzler says.
