Flea and scabies are parasitic STIs.
Who are the main groups affected?
Syphilis and tripping are most common in men who have sex with men.
The Robert Koch Institute estimates that at least four out of five reported cases of syphilis in Germany are transmitted through sexual contact between men.
In heterosexual adults, chlamydia infections, trichomoniasis, candidiasis (fungus), tripper and human papillomavires are common sexually transmitted diseases.
HIV prevalence among heterosexual adults in this country is comparatively low, yet they account for about 20 percent of new HIV infections.
Chlamydia infections are much more common among adolescents than in other populations.
According to European surveys, three quarters of all infections affect young people between 15 and 25 years of age.
In addition, the country has a high incidence of human papillomaviruses in adolescents.
How has the number of infections developed?
Not all sexually transmitted diseases are notifiable.
