On Saturday, Mexico's new president, Enrique Pena Nieto, will receive the presidential oath and assume leadership of the nation.
He is facing a complex task.
Mexico has been doing well economically under the outgoing government of Felipe Calderon, but the country is gripped by a drug war that has already claimed 60,000 lives in the past six years.
"My administration is strongly committed to reducing violence", Pena Nieto told US President Barack Obama in the Oval Office earlier this week.
I will propose a new security strategy to help us achieve this goal.
Before he was on par with the U.S. president, Pena Nieto served as governor of his home state of Mexico.
In this densely populated, sprawling part of the country surrounding the capital, opinions are divided about the new head of state.
A straight man
For example, in the remote town of Valle del Bravo, he is fondly remembered.
Residents of the resort attribute to it the development of tourism and the construction of infrastructure.
To reach the city, one can take one of the highways that Pena Nieto built, a major improvement over the brittle, bumpy roads that once existed.
His name is also displayed outside a modern sports centre and an impressive interactive museum on climate change.
"We expect real and lasting change from him", said his friend and political ally Gabriel Olvera Hernandez, a congressman for Pena Nietos' PRI party.
We hope that, in particular, in terms of security and the economy, we will see an interesting and real change, which our country so urgently needs.
After 81 years in power, the PRI was replaced by Vicente Fox in 2000.
Congressman Olvera admits that after 12 years outside the Los Pinos presidential palace, the party has high hopes for Enrique Pena Nieto.
The opposition's accusations that the new president lacks substance are rejected.
He was a very direct man, very committed and had big plans for the country.
He is an excellent statesman, but above all he is a good listener.
But on the other side of the state, not many people share that view of their former governor.
In Nezahualcoyotl, also known as Ciudad Neza, the contrast to the paved streets of Valle del Bravo could not be greater.
Hidden under highway crossings, the town is in many ways a suburb of Mexico City itself.
And the problems in the community are of a decisive urban nature.
Earlier this year, the military was called in to combat the neighborhood's drug gangs, and violence against women is a particularly acute problem.
In a patch of barren land near a large landfill, the bodies of dozens of murdered women have been left in the last two years alone.
During the term of Governor Pena Nieto, over 1,000 women were murdered in the state of Mexico - a statistic that even surpasses that of Ciudad Juarez, a city notorious for its violence and the murder of innocent women.
Pena Nieto's critics believe that he has not addressed the problem of female homicide adequately during his tenure.
But at worst, his government has turned a blind eye to the problem.
In a concrete building, typical of the slum, Irinea Buendia struggles with tears as she shows me photos of her deceased daughter Mariana Luna.
According to the official version of events, Mariana committed suicide in 2010.
But her family believes she was murdered by her partner.
"When I arrived at her home, it seemed as if her body had been washed", recalls Senora Buendia.
There were signs that she was beaten, and the rigidity had already set in.
While her mother tells her story, a picture of Mariana looks down at us from the wall, next to a cross that bears a single word: justice.
But that's what the family says she's been denied until now.
The authorities treated me like I was a gossip, a troublemaker, a whiner.
They want you to just accept their verdict and shut up.
"But that's not possible with so many misspellings and omissions", she says.
President Pena Nieto is taking on a great responsibility when he receives the presidential ribbon on Saturday.
Tens of thousands of Mexican families have been affected by violent crime in the last six years, and the new president has promised to take special care of this problem during his term in office.
"I hope that as president he will be like he was as governor", says PRI congressman Olvera in Valle del Bravo.
But that's what the families of the victims in Ciudad Neza fear most.
Prosecutors claim Bradley Manning never complained of abuse.
Prosecutors dispute Bradley Manning's claims that he was abused in prison.
The hearing will focus on Manning's time in the military prison at Quantico, Virginia.
The defense seeks a dismissal of the charges based on the harsh conditions of detention.
A U.S. Army private is accused of stealing thousands of classified documents.
Prosecutors tried Friday to establish that Army veteran Bradley Manning - accused of the largest leak of classified information in U.S. history - failed to complain about the mistreatment he allegedly suffered in military custody on several occasions.
In a cross-examination of Manning during a pre-trial hearing at Fort Meade, Maryland, Major Ashden Fein stated that records of weekly visits made by prison officials during Manning's nine-month detention at Quantico, Virginia, did not contain any complaints about his treatment.
A day before the cross-examination, which was held following a request by the defense to dismiss the charges - Manning had already been sufficiently punished by the harsh prison term - Manning had testified that he had considered suicide in prison.
The US Army intelligence analyst, arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of classified documents during his time in Iraq.
The material was then published by WikiLeaks on the Internet.
WikiLeaks never confirmed Manning as the source of the information.
At Friday's hearing, Fein reviewed with Manning the forms that officials had filled out after meeting with Manning during his detention at Quantico Military Prison, where he served time in enhanced conditions from July 2010 to April 2011.
The officers asked Manning questions and wrote down his answers.
When asked by Fein on Friday about the forms, Manning admitted that he had judged the treatment by his guards to be "excellent" and the treatment by the facility as a whole to be "very professional".
The forms, according to Fein, contained no complaints of abuse, even though the officers had directly questioned Manning about his treatment.
Manning replied that he had expressed his concerns orally and that officials had discussed them with him and said they would address them, but that they had not been recorded.
"They wrote down (after discussing the concerns) 'no problems', and that didn't necessarily mean I didn't say anything at all", Manning said.
The judge, Colonel Denise Lind, also asked Manning why he had not complained about his treatment when he met with a committee in January 2011 to investigate the suicidal thoughts he had mentioned on a form a few months earlier.
Manning replied that his intention during this meeting was to have his observation status downgraded to "prevention of injury".
The military said it assigned him this restrictive status - one level below the suicide risk - for his own protection and that of others.
"I wanted to convince staff that I was doing well and get rid of the injury prevention surveillance status (...) so that I could achieve what I think is a better quality of life", Manning said.
Manning testified on Thursday about his arrest and transfer to Kuwait, where he was held for nearly two months before being transferred to the prison at Quantico Naval Base in Virginia in July 2010.
He said that in Kuwait he considered suicide and once fainted from the heat.
Not knowing what was happening to him or to the outside world was stressful.
"My world shrank to Camp Arafjon, to this cage", Manning said Thursday.
I thought I was gonna die in that cage.
When he was transferred to Quantico, Manning spent most of his days in a small cell -- at least 21 hours and often more than 23 hours -- with no company.
All he was allowed was a mattress, a blanket, flip-flops, clothes and his glasses.
Manning said he tried to keep moving because during the day, he was forbidden to sleep or even lie down.
He was always forced to sleep with light coming from outside his cell.
When he turned around at night and the guards could no longer see his face, he was woken up to turn back.
In January 2011, Manning's lawyer formally filed a complaint against Manning's treatment.
In April 2011, Manning was transferred to the military prison at Fort Leavenworth, Kansas.
On Friday, Judge Manning also questioned him about a charge he had made in his testimony on Thursday, which involved sleeping naked in his cell at Quantico one night and standing naked in front of guards and other inmates during a morning count.
Manning had testified that he never had the opportunity to wrap himself in his blanket during that count.
During Friday's interrogation, Manning said he had been told by a guard to drop the blanket he could have covered himself with, but admitted that no one had asked him to.
On Thursday, Manning testified that he had been forced to sleep naked the night before, and that he had previously tried to show an officer that he posed no danger to himself.
Manning told the officer that he could have used the strap of his underwear or his flip-flops to injure himself, but he didn't.
That night, Manning testified, his underwear, flip-flops and glasses were removed from his cell.
His lawyers hope that the judge will at least take into account his prison experience and drastically reduce his sentence if he is convicted at his trial before the military court, which is scheduled for early next year.
The defense has indicated that Manning will plead guilty to lesser charges while other charges deemed too extreme will be challenged.
The prosecution is expected to justify the conditions of detention.
The Pentagon maintains its position that Manning was held in accordance with the regulations that apply to all detainees held under the highest security measures at Quantico.
Manning's charges include aiding the enemy, illegally posting classified information on the Internet, transmitting national defense information, and stealing public property or documents.
If he is found guilty on all charges, he faces life in prison.
My Mexican-American identity crisis.
Many people are forced to leave Mexico because of the lack of opportunities.
Mexicans tend to blame immigrants - they remind them of hard times, he says
Navarrette believes that Mexican Americans are caught between two worlds.
On a recent trip to Mexico City, I had just crossed the hall and arrived at passport control when I was startled.
Signs pointed to two queues: one for "Mexicanos" ("Mexicans") and another for "Extranjeros" ("foreigners").
I stood there for a few seconds, unsure which one to go to.
I grew up in central California and have been called a Mexican all my life.
An ethnic abbreviation -- just like my friends in Boston call themselves "Irish" or my friends in New York call themselves "Italian".
Later, I decided to go with Mexican-American.
But this was Mexico.
And in my grandfather's homeland, there was no need for shortcuts or binding.
I was just an American.
I speak Spanish, at least well enough to assert myself in that language at both ends of an interview.
But I don't have the vocabulary of a native speaker, and I can't get rid of my American accent either.
So I took my American passport and stood in line for the extranjeros.
I was thinking about that moment this week when the future Mexican president Enrique Pena Nieto visited the White House to meet with President Obama.
The agenda included all the issues that you would expect when the heads of these two countries meet: immigration, drugs and trade.
Pena Nieto was also very interested in talking about the growth of the Mexican economy, which is one reason why Mexicans today are just as likely to stay in Mexico as to emigrate to the United States.
He wants to ally himself with the United States and Canada and create a North American trade bloc modeled on the European Union.
And Pena Nieto vowed to continue Mexico's war against the drug cartels, though he gave no details.
Mexico's relationship with the United States is complicated and full of resentment.
Most Americans probably never waste a single thought on the fact that the United States invaded Mexico in 1848 and forced the country's leadership at gunpoint to give up more than half of its territory.
But for Mexicans who think in centuries, not minutes, memories of this event are not to be missed.
So whenever a U.S. government official makes even the slightest criticism of Mexico, complaints are heard - in the Mexican press and among the country's elites - about how Americans are threatening the sovereignty of their neighboring country.
And the children of Montezuma are going to war.
And yet Mexico's greatest challenge is actually its relationship with the more than 35 million Mexican Americans living in the United States.
You want to talk about resentment?
There's more than enough.
Mexico has winners and losers, people for whom the country offers opportunities and others for whom it does not.
The only reason so many people of Mexican descent live in cities like Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver, or San Antonio is because at some point in our family tree, someone -- maybe a parent or grandparent -- was not offered a chance in Mexico and migrated north.
And in most cases, this person matched a profile -- dark-skinned, uneducated, from a poor village, etc.
We are the descendants of those people, and our allegiance is to them.
Not Mexico.
And while we may be living the American dream now, going to good schools and getting good jobs, we must never lose sight of the fact that it is the American dream we are living, not the Mexican one.
Our identity may be blurred at times, but our loyalty is not.
This is clearly the case for the United States.
We are also aware that many members of the Mexican leadership do not like us.
This is based on reciprocity.
They see us as a reminder of a humiliating defeat and look down on us because we're not Mexican enough.
Our Spanish will never be good enough, our ties to Mexico will never be strong enough.
In their opinion, our existence is a symbol of failure.
If our families hadn't failed in Mexico, they wouldn't have left.
And then we wouldn't be trapped behind the silk curtain, living a comfortable life in the United States, but somehow lost.
My wife, who was born in Guadalajara and immigrated to the United States legally as a child, reminds me that there are tensions between Mexicans and Mexican Americans because Mexicans have a clearer idea of who they are -- and Mexican Americans resent that.
While she is an American citizen, she sees herself as part of two countries.
But many Mexican Americans I know feel that they don't belong to either country.
We love the Mexican band Los Tigres del Norte, but we also love Bruce Springsteen.
You enjoy the best of both worlds, but you're not rooted in either.
In Mexico, we're seen as Americans.
And in the United States, we're seen as Mexicans.
As I learned during my trip, there's something that makes this relationship even more complicated: some Mexican leaders and sections of the educated middle class want to reestablish their ties to the diaspora.
They want to use Mexican Americans as temporary "ambassadors" for Mexico to represent their interests in the United States.
We're supposed to tell our American colleagues how great it is to visit this country and put pressure on the political leadership to intensify their ties with Mexico.
Well, you know.
That's not gonna happen.
Too many hurt feelings.
And with the unequal distribution of income, rampant corruption, and drug violence, many of us are not so sure that this is really a great country.
I'm afraid you'll have to go through this alone, Amigos.
That's fair.
If at least some Mexicans are not yet ready to forgive the United States for its treatment of Mexico a century and a half ago, they must also accept that some Mexican Americans harbor resentment for the way their family members were treated not so long ago.
I'm not sure.
Maybe we're more "Mexican" than I thought.
Old battles, new Middle East
The ceasefire between Israel and Hamas could prove to be an unexpected pillar of peace
Can there ever be lasting peace between Arabs and Jews in the Middle East?
The latest bloody events seem to stifle such hope.
Amid the usual blame-sharing, countless buildings were destroyed, more than 140 Palestinians, mostly civilians, and six Israelis were killed - and for the first time, rockets from Gaza hit near the Israeli capital Tel Aviv and the holy city of Jerusalem.
But even though Israelis and Palestinians seem trapped in their historic conflict, the Middle East is changing around them.
The Arab Spring has created a new, uncertain situation, and whether they like it or not, Palestinians and Israelis have become part of that chaos.
Perhaps this will only lead to more bloodshed.
But there is reason to believe that the deadly impasse may finally be over.
A War Neither Lost nor Won
At first glance, optimism seems far from appropriate in the current situation.
Even if the ceasefire agreed on November 21 continues, this week's fighting has strengthened the hardliners on both sides.
The leaders of Hamas, the Islamist movement that has controlled Gaza since 2007, will claim to have pushed the Israelis back, even though their group itself has suffered heavy casualties.
Despite the deaths of several Hamas leaders and the confinement of the 1.7 million inhabitants of Gaza in one of the most desolate and densely populated corners of the planet, Israel has so far failed to destroy Hamas.
In fact, Hamas is gaining ground in the West Bank, which is controlled by the rival moderate Palestinian group Fatah.
And the Hamas leaders might conclude that time is on their side.
As Islamists have gained influence in the Arab world, Hamas has been able to draw powerful and wealthy friends to its side.
Turkey, a re-emerging regional power once considered Israel's closest Muslim ally, has sided with Hamas - as has Qatar, one of the richest and most dynamic Gulf states.
Cheering Hamas supporters believe that an Islamist crescent is forming around Israel - from Lebanon in the north, where militant Hezbollah is in power, to Syria, where increasingly Islamist rebels may face the overthrow of Bashar Assad, to Jordan, where Hamas allies threaten the king.
And in particular, the rise of the Muslim Brotherhood under President Muhammad Morsi in Egypt - by far the most populous and most important Arab country - on the southern flank of Israel has permanently changed the balance of the region.
Hosni Mubarak, the secularist despot who ruled Egypt for 30 years until his overthrow in 2011, had little time left for Hamas.
In contrast, the Brotherhood is allied with Hamas and its leaders are more dependent on popular opinion.
In future diplomatic negotiations, Hamas could prove to be an actor that even Israel and the United States cannot push out.
The Israeli hardliners, on the other hand, draw the opposite conclusion.
Militarily, Hamas is no longer a threat.
The Israeli missile defense system, Iron Dome, has proven itself and many of the Hamas missiles have been destroyed.
At least for a while, Israel will be able to sleep better.
The United States is firmly on its diplomatic position and many European countries have blamed Hamas for the latest escalation in violence.
Israel has done well in recent years, especially under Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, who has largely ignored the peace process.
Although rockets from the Gaza Strip have killed about 30 Israelis since 2004, the country has remained relatively free of suicide bombers, not least thanks to the barricades that run into the West Bank and the main part of a possible Palestinian state, which protect the Jewish settlements, which have been declared illegal under international law but are continuing to expand.
Netanyahu is in a good place, his Likud party has allied itself with an even more militant group ahead of the January 22 elections under Avigdor Lieberman.
Why should we also treat these treacherous Palestinians with kindness and give them their own state?
If they were in control of the West Bank, wouldn't they be firing rockets just like their comrades in Gaza?
No, it's better to keep them behind the wall and punish them if they dare to raise their heads.
The hardliners may be able to prevail, but the Arab Spring could wipe them out.
Even if the Islamists who are now in power in Egypt and other countries have little left for Israel, they will initially focus on the difficulties at home.
Israel's defense budget is larger than that of its four Arab neighbors put together.
A war with the local superpower will hardly help the new Arab governments in rebuilding their economies.
The fact that pragmatic President Morsi is teaming up with Barack Obama to achieve a ceasefire could be a promising sign - and perhaps symbolize the beginning of a new era.
Israelis should also think long-term.
While the rest of the Arab world is taking timid steps towards democratization, Palestinians continue to be denied their right to self-determination - a powder keg that will no doubt one day explode in the Israeli-occupied territories, just as a bus exploded in Tel Aviv this week.
The repression is already undermining democracy in the Jewish state, and as the Arab population grows, this situation will only get worse.
Bloody missions to repel Hamas in the Gaza Strip will increasingly take their diplomatic toll over the years.
Both sides need an outside push.
The correct answer is the one advocated by the more reasonable representatives of both sides, the rest of the world and this newspaper: two states, from which Israel cedes territory for security purposes.
The hope - small for the near future - is that the ceasefire will give outsiders more influence to enforce this solution.
Egypt must now join Turkey and Qatar in halting arms deliveries to the Gaza Strip and is in a better position than ever to convince Hamas of the idea of a Jewish state based on the 1967 borders, supplemented by a land swap and a shared Jerusalem.
The Arab nations outside should also try to get Hamas and Fatah to agree.
This would be more in favour of the creation of a Palestinian state than the upcoming application for UN observer status.
Obama too must do his part in moving Israel to negotiate.
During his first term, he failed to present his own peace plan.
Far from the White House, it seems he's equally reluctant to get involved.
But that is a sad, short-sighted prospect.
The United States has a vital interest in a stable Middle East.
And that includes a peace treaty between Israel and the Palestinians.
Australian laws on uniform cigarette packaging come into force
Health warnings and diseased body parts on neutral green packages identical for all tobacco brands
The world's first uniform cigarette and tobacco packaging laws have been introduced in Australia, replacing brand logos and colours with neutral olive green covers, which are also printed with drastic images showing sick body parts and babies and children affected by cigarette smoke.
Aside from the different health warnings and pictures, starting next Saturday, the only difference between the packages is in the brand names, which are printed in identical small print.
This introduces Australia's most stringent regulations on tobacco packaging in the world.
The Australian federal government wants to discourage young people from smoking by eliminating the glamorous image of tobacco use.
The government is based on studies that show that people who have not started smoking at age 26 are 99 percent likely not to start again.
"You can see from a young age that children understand the message that tobacco companies are trying to promote with their brand", says Federal Health Minister Tanya Plibersek, citing studies that have shown, for example, that children associate the crown of a logo with the idea of a princess.
Although Australia has one of the lowest smoking rates in the world and the changes will have little effect on the profits of multinational corporations, other countries are already considering similar steps.
The tobacco lobby fought hard against the laws.
The legislation was said to promote black market trade, leading to cheaper and more accessible cigarettes.
"The laws will have serious, unintended consequences", says Scott McIntyre of British American Tobacco Australia.
Chinese and Indonesian counterfeiters will be selling far more of these products on the streets of Australia.
Others, however, say that the laws have boosted their business.
Sandra Ha of Zico Import Pty Ltd, a small family business, notes that demand for cigarette cases and silicone lids to cover the intolerable packaging has skyrocketed since British American Tobacco, Britain's Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Japan Tobacco failed to challenge the laws in the High Court of Australia two months ago.
Zico has sold up to 6,000 units to wholesale stores and is waiting for new stocks.
It's a good deal for us.
Experts say the catch in the popularity of social media is precisely the population group the plan targets.
A series of Australian laws have banned tobacco companies from TV advertising, banned them from acting as sports sponsors, and forced most retailers to stop putting cigarettes in stores.
The Australian government has banned Internet advertising by local companies and sites, but has no influence on international sites.
"Anyone who markets tobacco and has only a small area to advertise their products doesn't get around the Internet", says Becky Freeman, a health researcher at the University of Sydney.
On social media such as YouTube, Twitter and Facebook, Freeman has seen an increase in brand testimonials written by "very normal people".
The question is: Is this just a private individual who likes Marlboro cigarettes so much that she even records a video for them - or is there a marketing agency involved?
British American Tobacco Australia says the industry is focusing on dealing with the new laws instead of marketing.
It has even gone so far as to pay Ukraine, Honduras and the Dominican Republic to challenge the new rules - countries that complain to the World Trade Organization about unfair trade restrictions even though none of them trade more with Australia.
A WTO decision is expected in mid-2013.
According to Plibersek, the government has been in talks with other countries that are considering similar packaging laws.
Canada was the first country to mandate photographic warnings in 2001.
These have now been extended to more than 40 countries, including Brazil, Turkey and Ukraine.
Tougher laws are being considered in Britain, New Zealand, South Africa and India.
Many Australian smokers are defiant.
The pictures don't affect me.
I just ignore them.
"You just take a cigarette and put the box away", says Victor El Hage about buying a pack of cigarettes with a picture of a mouth tumor printed on it.
Honestly, there's only one reason I'd quit, and that's my little girl.
James Yu, who runs the King of the Pack tobacco shop in Sydney's inner city, says the uniform packaging has made it difficult to fill his shelves.
"I used to take an hour to sort a shipment, now I need four", says Yu.
"The government should have just banned cigarettes altogether - then we would have said okay, that's it, we're closing", he adds visibly angry.
In a world that is always electrified, it's nice to be bored sometimes.
This Thanksgiving, I unexpectedly spent five hours at the airport when our plane failed due to mechanical problems and we had to wait for another plane.
So I had plenty of time to think about some boredom.
I don't want to lie.
Waiting half a day at the airport for a flight is pretty tiring - even when books, magazines and iPhones (and of course tax-free shopping) are available.
But more and more academics and child development experts are pointing to boredom as a positive.
If they're right, it's okay for us - and our kids - to be bored occasionally.
This forces the brain to lose itself in interesting thought processes, which may promote creativity.
And because most of us are staring at one screen or another almost all the time, we no longer enjoy the benefits of boredom.
So should we welcome boredom with open arms?
- I know.
And no, you didn't.
I shall return to that.
Like many people, I have always assumed that boredom is a relatively recent phenomenon that has evolved with increasing leisure time.
But Peter Toohey, professor of Greek and Roman history at the University of Calgary in Canada and author of Boredom: A Lively History (Yale University Press, 2011), sees things differently.
"In fact, boredom has a very long history", he says.
The walls of Pompeii's houses are adorned with Latin graffiti about boredom, dating back to the first century.
And then there's the question of how we actually define boredom.
According to John D. Eastwood, an associate professor of psychology at York University in Ontario, Canada, the problem is that boredom has been defined and discussed in many ways.
After a long reading of the research literature and presenting the idea to a focus group of about 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues concluded that boredom can be defined as the experience of "wanting to do something satisfying but not being able to do it".
Boredom differs from apathy in that the person is not busy but wants to be.
Apathy, on the other hand, is not an impulse to do something.
The key experience of boredom, he says, is a "disturbance in the attention process, coupled with a bad mood and a feeling that time is passing by slowly".
Boredom can almost sound like depression.
But Professor Eastwood believes that although these two conditions may be related, bored people see the problem in their environment or the world, while depressed people see the problem in themselves.
Sometimes we think we're bored, even when we just have trouble concentrating.
In their study "The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention", published in the September issue of Perspectives on Psychological Science, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues point to an earlier experiment in which participants listened to a tape on which a person read a magazine article.
Some groups heard a loud television program from the next room that had nothing to do with the content, others heard it at such a low volume that it was barely audible, while the third group heard none of the sounds at all.
The people who listened to the barely audible television reported feeling more bored than the other two groups - they had trouble concentrating, could not find a reason for it, and attributed their trouble to boredom.
When you try to concentrate on a difficult or strenuous task, attention deficit disorder can lead to boredom, says Mark J. Fenske, associate professor of neuroscience at the University of Guelph in Ontario and one of the study's authors.
On the other hand, when you do something monotonous - "like looking for defective products on a factory conveyor belt - music can be a distraction and help you to avoid feeling bored".
In fact, he says, we now know that groping and doodling, often interpreted as a sign of boredom, can even combat it by keeping people more physically alert.
"Studies have shown that children who are allowed to wander around learn more and retain more information than those who are forced to sit still", says Professor Fenske.
We all get bored at some point - my delayed flight, a thunderous speaker, a particularly tiring movie.
But some people get bored more easily than others.
To measure these differences, researchers developed a "boredom susceptibility scale" in the 1980s.
The scale includes statements such as "Many things I have to do are repetitive and monotonous" and "I have so many interests that I don't have enough time for everything".
Using such scales, researchers have found that boys are more likely than girls to be bored, says Stephen Vodanovich, a professor of psychology at the University of West Florida - especially when it comes to the need for more and a greater variety of external stimuli.
But in general, teenagers are a pretty relaxed bunch.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of human and community development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he contacted nearly 400 teenagers and their parents seven to eight times a day with a pager.
He found that 32% of teenagers were bored at school and doing their homework, while 23% reported being bored when they were not at school.
Yet only 3 percent of parents said they felt bored.
Professor Larson says today, 21 years later, he doesn't know whether the percentages of boredom have gone up or down.
He is, however, sure that "youth is perceived as particularly boring", mainly because children and teenagers have little influence over their daily routines.
So back to my original question: Is boredom healthy?
Sometimes not, because in extreme cases, it leads people to take extreme physical risks and to resort to gambling or drugs to alleviate them, studies have shown.
On the other hand, many philosophers and writers have studied the relationship between boredom and creativity, as has Professor Vodanovich, who has been researching the subject for more than two decades.
"Boring is a way for the brain to tell you to do something else", says Gary Marcus, a professor of psychology at New York University.
But the brain doesn't always know what's best to do right now.
When you're bored and you use that energy to play guitar and cook, you're happy.
But while television may produce feelings of happiness in the short term, these feelings fade in the long run.
So while handing a bored child an iPad may help him to get over his boredom, it has not taught him to entertain or control himself, says Professor Fenske.
He adds: "Self-control is a skill that is passed on from one situation to another".
Not only does the child learn to talk, but he also gains more self-control in other areas.
I don't think we should celebrate boredom.
We should also not be too critical of them.
Instead, our goal should be to feel comfortable outside the constant rush of activity and technology.
Professor Eastwood agrees with that.
"It sounds like we need to get bored more often, but boredom is the agonizing, incessant desire to do something meaningful", he says.
He believes that people are really just looking for a way to shut down and relax.
"In an environment where we are constantly over-stimulated, it is difficult to keep busy once the noise has subsided".
In Colorado , there is no clear guideline for the new marijuana law .
Nineteen-year-old community college student and football player Anthony Orozco is on trial in southeastern Colorado for a crime that will soon be legal in that state: possession of a few marijuana sticks and a pipe he used to smoke them.
According to Orozco, he and some friends were driving in Lamar, near the Kansas border, one day in September when they were stopped.
After the police officer found marijuana in the car, Orozco was subpoenaed for possession of drugs and drug paraphernalia - felonies punishable by a $100 fine each - and given a court date.
"We are treated like criminals", says Orozco.
But is he one?
In the uncertain weeks following the state's decision to legalize small amounts of marijuana for personal use, the answer to hundreds of minor drug offenses depends less on the law than on location.
Hundreds of marijuana-related offenses are already being dropped here and in Washington State, which has approved similar measures.
Police authorities will no longer prosecute adults over 21 for small-scale possession, which will be legal once the new laws come into force in the coming weeks.
But prosecutors in Colorado's more conservative counties have announced they're continuing to prosecute existing marijuana offenses and are still citing people in court.
At the same time, several cities, from the suburbs of Denver to the Western Mountains, are voting to ban new, state-licensed marijuana businesses from opening in their communities.
"This situation is moving so fast that I don't know what's going to happen next", says Daniel J. Oates, police chief in Aurora, east of Denver.
And regulators in Washington state are also scratching their heads.
They are waiting for guidance on setting up a licensing system for the production, manufacture, distribution and sale of the drug - and have a deadline of 1 December 2013.
In Washington, Colorado is considered to be ahead of most states in regulating marijuana, first for medical use and then for personal use.
"Colorado has a more regulated market, so the state is a good place to get a lead", says Brian E. Smith, spokesman for the Washington State Liquor Regulatory Commission.
But Smith also admits that no place or system can do more than serve in the sense of a rough guide.
"We have no real precedent to follow", he adds.
The Washington law, called I-502, goes into effect on December 6th, marking the end of a gray area where the state licensing system does not yet exist but possession is legal.
And uncomfortable practical issues need to be addressed during this time - such as how to reconcile the government's requirement for "reasonable access" to licensed marijuana with the ban on cannabis shops within 300 yards of schools, parks, playgrounds, and childcare facilities.
"Nowhere will it be harder to find a location for a licensed cannabis business than in urban areas, especially in the Seattle metropolitan area", says Ben Livingston, spokesman for the Center for Legal Cannabis, a recently formed research group.
On November 21, Chief Oates sent an email to his Aurora staff stating that the prosecutor would no longer prosecute minor marijuana offenses involving individuals over the age of 21, and that the police would not seek criminal charges for these offenses "immediately".
Chief Oates added that police would continue to enforce municipal regulations to regulate medical marijuana growers and continue to pursue drug dealers.
In Weld County in northern Colorado, District Attorney Ken Buck takes a more hardline view.
After the vote, he said his agency would continue to pursue marijuana possession cases, mainly to get users to quit.
Currently, 119 people face charges for possession of about 50 grams or less of marijuana, although many have been charged with other offenses.
"Our agency has a duty to prosecute violations that were criminal at the time of the offense", Buck said in a statement.
Reactions are mixed even in places like rural Mesa County, where voters rejected the marijuana initiative.
Police in Grand Junction, the county's largest city, no longer charge adults for possession of small amounts.
District Attorney Pete Hautzinger supported this decision, but also decided not to drop all outstanding property litigation.
"I don't think I'm wasting my time trying to enforce the law until it changes", he says.
Although 55% of Colorado voters supported the measure, it was clear from the beginning that it would not be easy to reconcile personal marijuana use with the complexities of government and the legal system.
And the conflicting reactions across the state fueled a deep division among local officials about the big green experiment.
For district attorneys, there is a "cultural barrier", says Sean McAllister, a Denver lawyer who represents marijuana offenders in court and is a local spokesman for the National Organization for the Reform of Marijuana Laws.
"They have spent so much of their lives prosecuting people for legalization that they still cannot accept it", he believes.
The first states to treat small amounts of marijuana like alcohol are Colorado and Washington, which are being touted as national models for legalizing drugs.
As advocates and government officials prepare for an era of legal marijuana sales, they are also anxiously awaiting directions from the federal government to continue to criminalize the sale and cultivation of marijuana at the federal level.
Advocates of the legalization movement hope the Justice Department will back down.
Despite several high-profile arrests of medical marijuana users and sellers, the federal government has largely allowed the sale of medical marijuana in Colorado, Washington and 16 other states.
Kevin A. Sabet, a former drug policy adviser to the Obama administration, believes that while criminal prosecutors are unlikely to break into doors to seize smaller quantities of the drugs, they are likely to be reluctant to tolerate legal, state-regulated marijuana businesses under the new legislation.
Several cities in Colorado aren't even waiting for federal authorities to act.
Even before election day, some local governments approved moratoriums on new marijuana businesses, even though they could not open for another year or so.
Last week, Montrose, a city in the west, passed a six-month ban, which will likely be passed next week.
"We don't want to get into a position where we license somebody and then have a big problem at the federal level", said city councilman Bob Nicholson.
Our community voted against this change in the law.
We are guided by what the community has decided, not by what the state has decided.
There are still many questions.
Petronella Wyatt: I was bullied from Oxford because I'm a Tory.
It is not only university students today who are attacked for their views
It had always been my greatest dream to get a place at Oxford University.
Both my father and my older brother had attended that university that I once thought was the greatest temple of knowledge in the world, a modern Greek symposium that promoted the great pillars of civilization -- free thought and tolerance.
But within two weeks of entering Worcester College in the late 1980's - where I had planned to study history - I had packed my bags again, and thus caused the first scandal of my life.
My father broke down in tears.
My friends were confused.
The Evening Standard said I left because I had a problem with classmates having sex in the next room.
Author A.N. Wilson mischievously explained that I had left the university because I was forced to drink from damaged cups.
But the truth was less amusing.
I ran away.
Yes, I did, because I was systematically bullied and threatened.
Not because of my rather unusual name, or because I came from a private school.
I had been bullied for one reason only - one that seemed all the more narrow and cruel in this supposed cradle of enlightenment: my late father, Woodrow Wyatt, had been a key adviser to Margaret Thatcher, and I was a supporter of the Conservative Party.
Why am I bringing this up now?
Well, recent reports are that a new generation of students on the moderate right is suffering similar persecution.
The organised and growing hatred of Tory students in Oxford has now reached such proportions that a group of them last week called for equal protection for gays, disabled and ethnic minorities.
Conservative members of the Junior Common Room (JCR) at Corpus Christi College say that because of their political views, they are "often actively isolated, personally attacked, and marginalized".
They're asking for a seat on their college's equality committee to ensure that their opinions can be expressed freely.
Their situation was made worse by a recent documentary about political students on BBC Two, Wonderland: Young, Bright and on the Right, which portrayed Tories as eccentrics and neo-Nazis.
It featured a graduate Joe Cooke, former president of the conservative Oxford University student union, in a Rolls-Royce, sporting a silver suit and silver-plated cane.
At other universities, conservative students say they are being considered "scapegoats for introducing higher tuition fees".
Luke Black, 20, vice-president of the conservative student union at Nottingham University, told a Sunday newspaper: "There is a growing left-wing tendency at universities.
People think we're like the Bullingdon Club without even knowing each other".
Samuel Roberts, 21, a history student in Corpus Christi who initiated the request for greater protection, believes such a climate is "unpleasant". 19-year-old Stephanie Cherill, president-elect of Oxford's conservative student union, says she has observed a growing rejection of moderate-right students among JCR members.
"This is a danger to intellectual discourse and to the wellbeing of members", she says.
In my first few weeks at Oxford, I was in that minority.
I arrived in September 1986 as an incredibly shy 18-year-old.
The hatred of the Conservative Party had reached its peak.
The university had voted last year to disqualify Margaret Thatcher - a former student - because of cuts in higher education.
The atmosphere would have scared even Stalinists.
In the first few days of the first semester, when new students get to know each other and the tutors, I got a taste of what was to come.
I found that the tutors not only tolerated the ridicule of Tory students, but even happily participated in it.
Political issues such as the miners' strike, privatization and the government's rejection of sanctions against the apartheid regime in South Africa found their way into the wooden-panelled rooms of the tutorials.
My first of these events was to translate 18th-century French texts into English, and I wasn't prepared for what was to come.
"Miss Wyatt", said the tutor Harry Pitt (now deceased), "translate the first paragraph, please".
I tripped.
Pitt was a little man with a face like cake dough, and quite obnoxious.
"Do Thatcherites refuse to learn French, or are they just stupid?" he asked me.
The other students chuckled.
Tears filled my eyes.
"I suggest you take a few French lessons in your free time - if you're not too busy with your social activities", Pitt growled at me.
I went back to my room with my head hanging down.
That night, I was sitting alone at the college dinner table when someone tapped me on the shoulder.
It was a second-year English student named James, who introduced himself as a member of the conservative student union.
"I know who you are", he said kindly.
Unfortunately, it is what it is.
Anyone suspected of being Tory is harassed.
It's bad enough for me, but they know your father's close to Margaret Thatcher, so it's gonna be worse for you.
Most Tory freshmen pretend to be Labour.
I tried to impersonate him later at a local pub.
I insisted that I did not agree with Mrs Thatcher on all points.
This trick was to prove unsuccessful.
A freshman in philosophy, politics and economics who had ironically attended Eton College, which was considered conservative, said to me, "You're the daughter of a fascist pig".
You're dirty. You're not clean.
Other students shared his opinion.
I was perverted and dirty.
"How do Tories have sex?" someone asked me.
They're beating each other up, aren't they?
I felt the way homosexuals must have felt before the more liberal legislation of the United States.
Would I ever be able to lead a normal life at Oxford University?
Would I be able to meet like-minded people after dark?
Should I turn to the Labour Party and have to suppress my natural inclinations?
The three years ahead of me stretched before my mental eye into a purgatory of banishment and isolation.
The only tutor who openly identified himself as a Tory was Norman Stone, a professor of contemporary history who was based at my college.
He was hated not only for being a conservative, but also for advising Thatcher on foreign policy and writing speeches for her.
He was rarely there.
He hated the place, found it provincial and petty, and rejected it for its Marxist-determinist historical perspective.
In 1997 he accepted a professorship at Bilkent University in Ankara, Turkey.
"You won't be happy here", he told me.
I began commuting between Oxford and my parents' house, and I found refuge with more open-minded friends and family members in the city.
I told my father that I hated Oxford and why I did it.
He seemed incredulous.
During his time in the 1940s, all political views were accepted.
"But it's the best place in the world", he said in a low voice.
They would never do that, not in my city of dream towers.
Even my Communist friends always had good manners.
His wet eyes were clouded.
Give it a chance.
I'm sure they're just teasing you.
It would break my heart if you left.
Exhausted by my frequent trips to London, my emotional resistance weakened.
One of my male friends, also a Tory, had given in to pressure and renounced his beliefs.
During a tutorial the following week, where another history teacher had seriously claimed that I was an "enemy of the people", I decided to do the same.
Although I was secretly ashamed, I admitted that my parents had brainwashed me, calling me "old fool".
The relief was short-lived.
It was my father who struck the final nail in the coffin of my Oxford career.
At the time, he wrote two columns a week for the Murdoch Press.
My door was locked.
I hid in my room, and after five minutes, my hoods gave up.
When they left, I packed a suitcase and took the first train to London.
I never came back.
You can call me a weeping limp.
But no 18-year-old should ever be subjected to such intimidation and malice in an educational institution.
And even more tragic is that it was Oxford -- a university that not only produced 14 Tory prime ministers, but that still hides behind an undeserved reputation for equality and freedom of thought.
"Valentino prefers elegance to fame"
On the occasion of the exhibition "Valentino - Master of Couture" which opened this week in London, ABC will speak with Naty Abascal, Fiona Thyssen-Bornemisza and other famous clients of the Italian fashion designer.
Somerset House, the former residence of Elizabeth I of England, is the only place in the British capital worthy of hosting an exhibition about Valentino Garavani.
This was acknowledged by the designer at the opening of Valentino - Master of Couture, a grand retrospective that features more than 130 Haute Couture dresses created by his "Maison" over the past 50 years.
"I love this palace", he says with his distinctive Italian accent.
This exhibition is the conclusion of a story whose only protagonist is "il signore" Garavani, but which could not have been written without his distinguished clientele.
Valentino has always been fascinated by the stifling and distant world of the nobility.
In the first hall of this exhibition, which will be on view until March 3, there are a number of private letters and photos signed by the most distinguished aristocracy, from Princess Salimah Aga Khan, Princess Marie-Chantal of Greece and Margaret of England to Lord Snowdon.
Valentino shows these personal memories as trophies of his social rise from humble fashion designer in the northern Italian city of Voghera to international jet set idol.
Being in love with the nobility doesn't have to be a disadvantage.
"At least they don't kick their dicks out on your gorgeous carpet like some beautiful pop stars do", says Baroness Fiona Thyssen-Bornemisza.
In the 60s and 70s, the two lived in the Alps and were good friends.
Valentino is a spectacular, generous and elegant host.
"We were all very happy to be invited to his house in Gstaad", explains the ex-wife of "Heini" Thyssen, who is close friends with forgotten beauties such as Marella Agnelli and Eugenie Niarchos.
Valentino has always preferred elegance to fame.
And yet he's a star.
Valeria Mazza, in a dress by Valentino
The Argentine model Valeria Mazza also remembers the charisma of the fashion designer.
Many years ago, after a fashion show in Piazza di Spagna in Rome, we went to his house for dinner.
We were about 20 people, including Sharon Stone and John Kennedy Jr.
Every detail of his apartment, the decorations, the food and the music, was recognizable and felt his influence.
"All the guests felt important and loved", recalls the "top model", who started her career at the 1995 Paris haute couture week.
"He never goes out of style because his designs are works of art", she concludes.
Fashion show of origin
Garavani's life is not a story of obsession, but of mutual love.
He likes people with good manners and the highest titles, and they love him.
One of the galleries at Somerset House has been transformed into a glorious, 200-foot-long runway that offers a role-change: the user takes the role of the model and walks along the runway to admire a dreamlike "audience" wearing Valentino's masterpieces, such as the dress Jackie Kennedy chose for her wedding to Aristotle Onassis, the costumes Monica Vitti wore in "La Notte", or a wool and leather coat that belonged to Empress Farah Diba.
In this audience of fashion dolls, names such as Sibilla of Luxembourg, Gloria of Thurn and Taxis, Mette-Marit of Norway, Rosario of Bulgaria or Sofía of Habsburg radiate.
Naty Abascal and the fashion designer, 2006
Many of these customers say that the first Valentine is like the first love, "unforgettable".
I remember perfectly.
It was a pair of pants, a shirt, a vest of the "Gillette" type and a jacket from the autumn/winter 1971-72 collection.
"It was a gift from him", says Naty Abascal, one of the designer's muses.
"I prefer him to everyone else because of his great love for women and because he brings out our beauty", adds the ex-Duchess of Feria.
I like the colors he uses very much; they have a lot of light and emphasize the face.
The proportions are perfect.
The princess and fashion icon Patricia della Giovampaola d'Arenberg can't forget the first time she wore a Valentino.
When I was a teenager living in Italy, I dreamed of finally being old enough to wear one of his evening dresses...
In the late 1990s, it finally came to pass.
I bought my first Valentino dress for a party at my cousin's castle, Prince Edouard de Ligne.
It was a red dress with a flying skirt and a draped top with a decollete that honors his name.
"It was a dream come true", says the widow of Rodrigo d'Arenberg.
"Valentino is not fashion-dependent, his obsession is timeless", explains this Italian aristocrat who lives between Paris, New York, and Buenos Aires.
The Princess of Arenberg keeps her evening dresses from the fashion designer "with absolute care", "because a dress is not just a dress, but also the memories associated with it".
The "King" of Fashion
The grand finale of the exhibition at Somerset House is the wedding dress of Marie-Chantal Miller for her wedding to Pablo de Grecia in 1995.
Four months of work and 25 "girls" (as the fashion designer called his seamstresses) were needed to make this ivory-colored silk dress with pearls, twelve different embroidery and a four-and-a-half-meter-long tail.
According to journalist Suzy Menkes, the leading authority on the trade press, this dress was a milestone in haute couture in the late 20th century, "the return to the customers of the upper society".
After years of being marred by the elite's "savoir-être", Valentino is now their best example.
Cavaliere di Gran Croce (the highest award in Italy), Cavaliere del Lavoro, Commandeur de L'Ordre des Arts et des Lettres, decorated with the Legion of Honor, Garavani accumulates as many honors as any of the husbands of his clients.
"I have always been impressed by his refinement, his calmness, his neat and perfect appearance", admits D'Arenberg.
I saw him last a month ago at a gala dinner at the Musée d'Orsay.
He was sitting at the table of the Countess Jacqueline de Ribes, a very good friend of mine.
"He was flawless; time leaves no trace of him".
And this is from a princess...
The world's toughest job: the human work animals of Kawah Ijen
For four euros, the volcano's carriers risk their lives and health to carry 70 kilograms of sulfur over steep rocky paths.
There are people for whom their work is hell, and others who work literally in hell.
This is the case of Anto Wijaya, one of 400 miners who earn their living by extracting sulfur from the Kawah Ijen volcano on the eastern Indonesian island of Java.
To do this, he has to climb down to the bottom of his crater every day, where the sulfur gas emitted from the earth solidifies in contact with the air.
After breaking large stones of sulfur, which can weigh up to 130 pounds [70 kg], he carries them in two bamboo baskets on his shoulders over the steep stone paths.
Although it is only a quarter mile to the top of the volcano, which rises to an altitude of 8,050 feet [2,386 m], the weary carriers take more than 40 minutes to ascend at turtle-like speed, balancing and carefully setting their steps so as not to slip and fall.
They know that every step can cost them their lives, as happened to a French tourist who crashed years ago on the slopes of Kawah Ijen.
The miners of Kawah Ijen earn 5 cents for every kilo of sulfur they extract.
Once at the top, they cut their way through the tourists who photograph them like circus monkeys and run the gruelingly heavy baskets three kilometers to the scale that a mining company has set up a little further down at an altitude of 1,850 meters
The company is PT Candi Ngrimbi, which has been exploiting the volcano's resources and (never better) its workers since 1960, paying 662 Indonesian rupees (5 eurocents) for each kilo of sulfur.
They then sell it to the petrochemical industry for 10,000 rupees (83 cents), because the mineral is widely used in everyday life to make matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite, and even sugar bleach.
"We usually carry 70 kilograms [70 lb], so we get about 46,000 rupees [US$3.80, U.S.] each way", explains Anto, who usually makes three trips a day.
He takes three hours to complete each run, and by the end of the day, he has 138,000 rupees.
What seems like a miserable reward for such a barely human effort is three times what he would earn from field work.
"The daily wages of the miners here, who are paid 15,000 rupees ($1.50) a day for the coffee harvest and earn an average of two million rupees ($1.90) a month, are very high", explains the porter, who formerly worked as a mason on the tourist island of Bali.
There he earned 75,000 rupees (US$6.2), and the work was not so hard, but Anto returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a nearby village, for a reason that is as important in Indonesia as sulfur: "I married a girl from Bali, where they are Hindus, and I took her to Java to convert her to Islam".
Anto has asthma, breathing difficulties, frequent coughs and irritated eyes from the toxic gases.
For three years, 27-year-old Anto has been risking his life at Kawah Ijen, where sulfur has already left its first traces on him, although he covers his face with a mask and special glasses.
Anto has asthma, breathing difficulties, frequent coughs and eyes irritated by the toxic gases from the volcano.
This is the price he has to pay for achieving his dream.
"I'm going to work here for two more years because I want to open a shop or learn Spanish or French", he promises in more than acceptable English.
This nice and intelligent young man, but under sentence of life, could be a tour guide, a waiter, or a hotel receptionist, but instead he's doing the job of a porter.
He shares a dirty wooden hut with other carriers and gets up at two o'clock every morning because the sulfur also flows out at night, where its characteristic yellow color glows blue in the dark.
Challenging the shadows, he climbs into the crater in the light of a small headlamp on his helmet, which he bought with his own money.
About 400 carriers load the baskets of sulfur on their shoulders at the crater floor.
Despite its large profits, the mining company has not mechanised sulphur extraction to save costs and has not supplied any equipment to the miners, who work on their own account and are paid by weight.
They also do not receive the 30,000 rupees ($1.50) camera fee that the park's guards charge, along with the 15,000 rupees ($1.50) entrance fee for tourists who come to photograph the volcano and the human torso.
"This work is for animals and not for people", protested Madrusin, a 42-year-old carrier who has been working at Kawah Ijen for three decades since leaving school.
He is able to carry up to 110 kilograms and says he will continue "as long as he can", because he needs the money to raise his three children, ages 10 to 18.
I'm not retiring. I'm dying here because the volcano was my whole life.
Even when the sulfur burns the throat and itches the eyes, when the wind suddenly turns and the miners are trapped in the thick columns rising from the crater, the men are so tough that no one complains of serious illnesses... except, of course, the usual breathing problems, arthrosis, pain in the knees and blisters on the shoulders that have deformed from the weight of the baskets.
With the basket on his back, Unainik, at 53 years old, is only able to carry 50 kg.
Each day, he and his companions break 15 tons of sulfur from the volcano, which is transported by three trucks along a goat trail through the bush to the Tamansari camp, 11 miles [18 km] away.
"I'm not retiring, I'm going to die here because the volcano was my whole life", Unainik explains, opening his mouth wide, missing some teeth.
The eldest of his five children, at age 30, also works as a sulfur carrier.
Time passes, but the poverty continues generation after generation in one of the hardest jobs in the world: that of those who work as human burden-bearers on the Kawah Ijen.
Singapore needs babies to save the economy
Singaporeans blame their lack of children on their careers, stress, and the cost of real estate and child rearing.
"Singapore's population needs to grow".
I am a patriot husband, you are my patriot wife: let us fulfill our civic duty and create life!
It seems incredible that the verses are part of a mint candy commercial, but even so - or because of that - they went viral on YouTube earlier this year in Singapore.
The phrases are part of a rap song that uses local sayings such as "Showing a bao in the oven is a way of mocking the low birth rate in Singapore.
The advertising company BBH, which shot the video, hopes that the commercial will bring attention to the problem in a fun way.
Its creative director Douglas Hamilton says he wanted to use the power of music to get people to do their "national duty".
This is just for the Internet, so we had to make it fun and funny.
It is the biggest problem in this country.
We're the worst in the world at reproduction, so we realized that this was an issue we needed to address.
We knew that the government had tried many things, such as marketing pheromone perfume or organizing speed dating evenings.
Many of these ideas may have been creative, but they didn't necessarily lead to success.
So we thought, why not do something as creative as possible to address this problem, like compose a rap?
Children 1.2
The Singapore government is the one who is not taking this issue lightly.
Every year, it spends $1,300 on policy measures to encourage citizens to have more children.
A government package for couples and parents provides up to $15,000 per child, extends maternity leave and distributes tax benefits.
But so far, little has been achieved.
Singapore is a wealthy, high-tech city-state in Southeast Asia, also known for the conservatism of its rulers and its strict social controls.
According to its national population agency, the birth rate is currently 1.2 children per woman.
The last time this rate was above 2 - also known as the replacement rate - was in 1976.
So why aren't Singaporeans having more children?
Wei Tan Ming, director of marriage and family policy at the National Population Agency, says this is due to "better education" and "greater career opportunities".
"This has allowed people to have much more options in terms of goals and priorities in life, in addition to getting married and starting a family", she explains.
These changes in social conditions have contributed to the higher number of single people and to the delay in marriage and birth, which has resulted in a decrease in the birth rate in Singapore.
Meanwhile, an immigration policy aimed at drastically increasing immigration to counter population decline has led to resentment among the local population.
In Singapore, there are websites that have a thinly veiled xenophobia against many new immigrants, especially the Chinese, who are criticized for keeping wages low and not integrating.
The rise in immigration is also seen as one of the reasons why Singapore's ruling party scored its worst election result since independence last year.
Since the elections, an attempt has been made to correct the problem by increasing contributions and taxes for foreign workers.
Unexpected Consequences
While falling birth rates have known effects on a nation's economic growth, tax revenues, health care costs, and immigration policies, the example of Singapore also shows unexpected consequences.
The government is trying to make sure that not so many small apartments are built.
It is already having an impact on the housing market.
The Urban Development Authority has begun to control the number of small apartments, known as "shoe boxes", that are allowed to be built in certain areas of the city.
These apartments have a living area of 46 square metres and are very successful.
However, there is concern that they may encourage the single-person lifestyle and discourage construction companies from building large homes for families.
But Lim Yew Soon, general manager of real estate firm EL Developers, says his "shoe boxes" sell much faster than larger units.
They're so popular, and the units sell out days and even weeks faster than the larger units.
This makes them much better for our cash flow.
He admits, however, that the new standards give clearer guidance to developers who have previously been hindered when they wanted to build too many small housing units within a project.
Too much stress
Singapore is a city-state.
Even if these new rules could pave the way for a rise in the national birth rate, conversations with Singaporeans working in the financial sector suggest that they will not have much effect.
"People are under a lot of stress, housing is expensive, and education is expensive, so many people are putting it off", says one young manager.
The kids can have others.
"It's important to me to have my own money and time", says another man in his early twenties.
Men and women cite their careers, stress, and the cost of property and education as reasons for not having children.
That is why Singaporeans have the final say when it comes to having children - there is so much the government can do.
The offline private offline is online private
Privacy
According to the dictionary, it is the property of privacy, or "that area of one's private life where one is entitled to protection from any interference".
What's private for someone under 16?
How does this definition apply to his daily life and social networks?
Does he understand the dangers he is exposing himself to by posting things on the Internet that he would not share in real life?
El Periódico interviewed five teenagers aged 10 to 15 who are frequent users of the Internet.
In four of the cases, they associated the term with "something very personal" at a personal level and "on the password and the user" when applying it to social networks.
"I wouldn't reveal my deepest secrets in a post", says 10-year-old Jorge, trying to explain the meaning of "private" on sites like Facebook, Twitter, Hotmail and Windows Live Messenger, where he has had accounts for two years.
"These are very confidential secrets, my mother may know them, but not the whole world", he confirms.
I'm posting pictures of pretty things on FB or games.
I also spend my time with friends.
"I wouldn't share a photo that wasn't of me or someone who was being a jerk", he says.
The boy is well aware that it is wrong to post obscene photos, of naked people, of crimes, or to write offensive or violent comments.
Jorge claims to have 35 friends on Facebook and nine followers on Twitter.
Most of them are relatives.
Including the mother who has the password to one of the accounts.
I logged on to Twitter to express myself and write interesting tweets.
"I don't know if anyone will answer me, I just upload them", he adds.
"Social networks are fun, and I can quickly talk to distant relatives or friends", he says.
When asked, he replies that he would never accept an invitation from a stranger.
Even if someone recommended a stranger, he would ignore it.
The case of 14-year-old José is different.
The teenager has user accounts on Hotmail, Facebook, My Space and Ask, and in Ask he admits not knowing 20 of the people he added to his friend list.
"That doesn't scare me because we have something in common, like music", he says.
According to the boy, no one hinted at him or asked for his address or telephone number.
"If someone harasses me or asks me to do it, I simply remove them from my user account", he admits.
José contacted Ask after reading a recommendation on Twitter.
The boy is not unfamiliar with what is now known as cyberbullying.
A friend's friend was blackmailed on a social network.
They threatened him and demanded money.
"He never knew who it was", he assures us.
According to José, the victim didn't close the user account.
"He was just doing it privately".
It then explains a series of steps to configure a user account securely.
Unlike Jorge, this youngster would upload photos of people he knew in awkward or embarrassing situations.
Yeah, I would if he was unpleasant or I wanted to kick his ass.
"But I know it's cyberbullying", he explains.
The key questions
Marielos Porras, an English teacher with a university degree in education and learning, believes that to guide children and young people, it is necessary to understand that the purpose of social networks is to inform.
"The Internet was created as a medium for finding information, but with the advent of these sites, the rules of the game have changed", she says.
Porras explains that academic Marc Prensky, a master's degree holder in education at Yale University and author of the book "Digital Natives and Immigrants", coined these terms to explain the phenomenon.
The digital natives are them, the children and teenagers who grew up with this technology.
"We are the digital immigrants who are supposed to teach them when we are still learning", he says.
He explains that this is a complex issue "because we are asking them to have a defined criterion of what can be spread, published or said at an age when maturity is not sufficient".
"They should also be picky when it comes to being popular, having thousands of friends, without thinking about the consequences", he adds.
According to the expert, the most effective way to teach children and teens about privacy is to ask them thought-provoking questions.
