Conclusion of the UNASUR Summit without publication of the Lima Declaration
The sixth summit of the presidents of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) ended today in Peru without the publication of the Lima Declaration, which had been announced earlier and was supposed to be signed by the seven leaders present.
Efe repeatedly tried to gain access to the signed document at the VI Ordinary Meeting of Heads of State and Government of Unasur.Sources in the State and Presidential Office initially said they would hand it over after the examination, but later stated that it would be published on the Peruvian government website at some point.
When asked about the text, they said that the content was presented by the President of Peru, Ollanta Humala, in brief statements to the press.
The access of journalists to information about the summit was limited at all times.
During the day, the press room only broadcasted the picture of the presidential meeting without sound with the message "private session, limited audio".
The few pieces of information that were circulating among journalists were obtained by the press officers of some of the UNASUR governments present at the meeting, but not by the Peruvian press officer.
The only document circulated during the day was the list of the participating presidents, which caused discomfort among the hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who demanded more information.
The Peruvian presidency then sent an email to the media with the summit's "concluding statement", but it was Humala's statement and not the official document concluding the summit.
Last October Peru hosted the third Summit of South American Arab States (SASA) and, despite press calls, the so-called Lima Declaration announced earlier was not published.
The official website of the ASPA shows that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities stressed that information systems were in place for journalists, but they severely restricted access to information.
The summit also ended with the joint commitment of Chile and Peru to accept a judgment of the Court of Justice of the Hague which settles a border dispute between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met during the regional meeting and confirmed that they would accept the decision of the International Court of Justice, which opens Monday in The Hague, to hear the pleas of both sides in the Lima v. Santiago trial.
"We will follow and implement the judgment on the differences we are presently presenting to this international court", Humala said along with his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile was, is and will remain a country that respects international law, seeks peaceful solutions to disputes, concludes agreements and submits to international courts", Piñera added, shaking hands with Humala in front of the flags of both countries.
The two presidents confirmed their submission to the ICC after Colombia filed a complaint against the Bogota Convention following a decision on the maritime borders with Nicaragua which it considered a grave error, agreeing to submit to the judgments of that international court.
The summit was attended by the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff, Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, Bolivia, Evo Morales, and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, which has been excluded from Unasur since the 2011 ouster of its president Fernando Lugo, did not attend the meeting.
The host President Ollanta Humala opened the talks in the morning and concluded the summit in Lima shortly after noon.
The Head of State read the final document, in which he announced that 16 decisions had been taken and the lines of action for 31 projects between the South American countries had been defined, with a total investment of 17 billion dollars.
He said the decisions taken by the UNASUR countries would "take important steps towards the goal of South American citizenship, to which we extend the Residence Decisions".
He said that action would be taken to "improve cooperation in the fight against urban insecurity and organised transnational crime, and to improve access to low-cost medicines and the Internet in all areas of South America and to act jointly and efficiently in the event of natural disasters".
With the crisis in Europe, "economic consolidation (in Latin America) must not take a triumphant turn, but serve to expand our production capacity and show our peoples a better future", Humala added.
"We have decided to give priority to a series of 31 emblematic projects to improve spatial connectivity in South America, especially in rural and border areas...thus uniting our countries and opening up new economic forms", the Peruvian president said in a statement read out.
Among these projects were five Peruvian projects, which are located on the cross-axes of his territory from the coast to Brazil, and two of which are to provide better connectivity with Ecuador, although he did not give further details.
The final document also referred to the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process in this country will serve its reintegration into the Union of South American Nations", from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain an integrated region of prosperity and peace and good neighbourly relations was another aspect emphasised at the summit.
In this regard, the President of Colombia, Juan Manuel Santos, said before he began his participation in the regional meeting that he expected to meet his Nicaraguan counterpart, Daniel Ortega, in Mexico on Saturday to deal with the maritime conflict respectfully following a ruling by the ICC that was questioned by Bogotá.
"I will probably meet with President Daniel Ortega tomorrow (Saturday)", Santos said.
He said that the EU had to be prepared to take on board the new challenges and that the EU had to be prepared to take on board the new challenges.
"I hope to be able to tell President Ortega that we will handle this matter as civilized and respectful as possible", Santos added.
Santos and Ortega are due to meet in Mexico on Saturday, where they intend to attend the inauguration of the country's new president, Enrique Peña Nieto.
As part of the summit, the bloc's defence ministers also met in advance to adopt the 2013 action plan to strengthen dialogue and consensus on the region's defence.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay are members of UNASUR, although the latter is currently excluded.
Peru holds the provisional presidency of the regional bloc.
"South America must learn from the integration of its citizens", says Rafael Correa
The President of Ecuador, Rafael Correa, today confirmed that the creation of a common citizenship is a goal, with which "South America can actually learn something from Europe".
Correa, who attended the 6th Summit of Presidents of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) in Lima, told Peruvian state television that Europeans "killed each other in World War II and other conflicts" and "are practically a homeland today".
In this sense, he defended the project of creating a South American citizenship that the member states of Unasur are pushing forward.
'Freedom of movement for citizens and workers must be achieved in all South American countries, as is already the case in the Andean Community, but there are still reactionary sectors that want to return to the past,' he warned.
The President of Ecuador also supported the reorganization of the Organization of American States (OAS) with the aim of reducing the influence of Anglo-Saxon countries and taking into account those that have signed the San José Convention on Human Rights.
The teachers never make a commitment, and in return, we South Americans always sign everything.
"It is incomprehensible that the Inter-American Commission on Human Rights is based in Washington and is funded by the United States", he said, referring to the political asylum granted by Ecuador to WikiLeaks founder Julian Assange.
Correa assured that he did not regret this decision because he did not betray his principles, but he followed his "deep democratic values and views on human rights".
He added that at the time there were 'reasonable grounds to believe that Assange would be extradited to a third country and his case would not be followed'.
He also criticised the Swedish judiciary for requiring him to be interrogated on its territory for an alleged sexual offence, while 'Swedish law allows this to be done by videoconference, which could have been done via the Ecuadorian embassy in London'.
Correa explained that there was a risk that Assange's health and mental state would be affected.
"I have not spoken to him since he arrived at our embassy, but the ambassador informed me that he has a mild lung problem, but not a serious one", the Ecuadorian head of state said.
However, there is a risk of physical and psychological harm because he is confined in a confined space and cannot exercise outdoors.
"This would affect the health of every person", he added.
Correa said the solution to the asylum granted to Assange since June at the Ecuadorian embassy in London was to grant him a free pass to travel to Ecuador, and that this was in the hands of Britain, Sweden and the legal authorities of Europe.
We are not dealing with human rights, we do not use that word in this case, but there have been constant discussions.
"The solution to this problem is in the hands of the UK, Sweden and the European legal authorities because Assange's lawyer, Baltazar Garzón, is conducting a series of proceedings in different European courts", he explained.
And if Britain grants this waiver tomorrow, I think that's settled.
And if Sweden interrogated Mr Assange at the Ecuadorian embassy in London or via Skype, as Swedish law allows and has been done in other cases, the problem is solved.
Correa took the opportunity to assert himself as a defender of press freedom, saying that what he does not tolerate is "the mediocrity, the malice and the lies that undermine freedom of expression".
"The greatest enemies of press freedom are not the evil and perverse politicians, but bad journalists who seek profit and blackmail", he said.
In this sense, he congratulated himself that Ecuador is no longer ruled by such journalists "nor by the bankers or hegemonic and squat bourgeois countries", and predicted that if re-elected "he will deepen the revolution to continue on the path in this right direction".
Correa also supported the decision to maintain the veto against Paraguay in Unasur at least until its next elections, arguing that the body "must remain tough and must not give in to opportunism and a coup disguised as legal" because it "destroyed the legitimacy of democracy in Paraguay".
The President of Ecuador also considers that his Colombian counterpart, Juan Manuel Santos, is 'absolutely justified' in wanting to negotiate with Nicaragua the maritime boundaries between the two countries now and after the judgment of the International Court of Justice in The Hague, which favoured Nicaragua's maritime sovereignty.
This judgment is not currently being implemented.
It is a problem between a South American and a Central American country.
Conflicts are inevitable, but they must be overcome in the pursuit of a common path.
They need to be addressed comprehensively so that they can be overcome and looked at in the future.
He also hoped that the disputes over the maritime borders between Peru and Chile would be settled by the same court, saying that "it is right for Latin America to appeal to international bodies if both countries commit to accept the judgment, even if it is very harsh".
Regarding the possibility of him running for the next presidential election in Ecuador to achieve his third consecutive term, he said he sees this possibility "with great optimism and joy, although it is sometimes very difficult".
Correa has assured that if he loses the elections in February 2013, he will retire from political life.
I have never personally been interested in power, but in such unjust circumstances as in Ecuador, this socioeconomic poverty can only be corrected by political power.
"My political movement believed that I was the one who guaranteed this probable victory, so I have to fulfill this responsibility", he said.
If I win, it would be my last term as president, after which I will retire from public life.
This is true even if we lose.
"That's decided", he explained.
Correa also referred to the treatment of the health problems of Venezuelan President Hugo Chávez in Cuba.
I just spoke to the Vice President of Venezuela, Nicolás Maduro, and he told me that he had traveled there for a scheduled, routine treatment, and that he was expected to be able to travel back to Cuba after the election campaign.
"It does not in any way mean a relapse in President Chávez's health", he commented.
