The cause of one AIDS death today is too late to be identified
Fabrizio was 21 years old when his test result was confirmed: HIV positive.
"It was like a bomb went off", he says of the moment he received the diagnosis, which the doctor tried to "weaken" with no apparent success.
He hid it from his family.
He decided to take care of his illness on his own and began to educate himself about it, and he did so with such dedication that he had just celebrated his 43rd birthday.
He is undoubtedly one of the oldest patients in the HIV unit of the Hospital Civil de Guadalajara (HCG), where he entered in 1994 after several struggles.
Fabrizio has been living with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) for 22 years, which was hard to imagine in the early 1990s when there were many doubts, few treatment options and more stigma.
At the time, even the director of one IMSS clinic avoided saying goodbye "because it led to a dead end".
Back then, AIDS was synonymous with death.
Today, it is possible to survive this syndrome with quality of life.
However, many people still come to the clinic unaware of their illness, and in whom the virus has already done damage and depleted their immune systems, and who are victims of opportunistic infections.
Thirty-one years after the world's first reported cases of AIDS, "the great success today means that the survival of a patient who starts treatment on time is exactly the same as that of the general population", said Jaime Andrade Villanueva, head of the HIV Unit at the HCG, adding that this information was backed up by a respected scientific publication in April of this year.
Infectious diseases and HIV/AIDS expert Andrade Villanueva said that scientists have concluded since 2008 that while AIDS is not a death sentence, the years of survival and quality of life depend on the degree of impairment of the people's immune system when they start treatment, and that those who are not drug-dependent have a better chance: up to 30 years with a CD4 count of 200 and 50 years with a CD4 count of 500.
Simply put, the above statements mean that a person diagnosed HIV-positive at age 25 can "live to be 75 without any problems, as long as it is under control", he explained.
To properly classify this progress, it must be remembered that the average life expectancy of Mexicans today is 76 years.
Even though the death rate has fallen significantly in recent years (in Mexico, the number of AIDS deaths has decreased from 6,678 in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (UNAIDS annual report), it is true that since the onset of AIDS, 60 percent of the patients in the national database have died.
In Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011, and as of May this year, 187 have died, but it is assured that since 2005 there has been universal access to antiretroviral drugs.
- So why are people still dying?
- In my opinion, the problem is not access to treatment.
This is my opinion, and this is how it is in our hospital.
At least in the last 12 years, we have not had a problem with the supply of medicines, but the problem is that people come in very advanced stages because they don't know their infection, which is very late stages of the disease.
He makes a striking statement: "Nine out of 10 patients come to us with an underlying infection, and to affect global mortality, we need earlier detection, which means that we need to offer massive screening to all those who need it".
This proposal is supported by the experts and officials of the Consejo Estatal de Prevención del Sida en Jalisco (Coesida) (State Committee for the Prevention of AIDS in Jalisco) and also by patients like Fabrizio, who had his test done in a private laboratory, for the sole reason that it had made a friend of his who, despite his young age, was already in the AIDS phase and even had Kaposi's sarcoma (a cancerous tumor), one of the common complications.
Everything's different when you know you have AIDS.
Some people think they're going to die, and they don't want to hear anything.
"If I have to die, I'd rather burst three times", they say in my case.
The change was to better myself, I eat well, exercise and take my medication.
Today, his parents only know that he had cancer.
I live a normal life, like everyone else.
"I work, I do a lot, I have an active but responsible sex life, I take care of my health and the health of the other person", says Fabrizio, who agreed to share his intimate details with MILENIO JALISCO to encourage those who are afraid today on World AIDS Day.
They should get tested if they're at risk, and the sooner they know if they're HIV positive, the better, and if they already know the diagnosis, they should learn how to live responsibly like everyone else.
His message is a summary of the fight against AIDS in 2012.
Condoms behind the counter
There are huge gaps between health programs and the average citizen, explains Ricardo Salazar, a journalist from Guadalajara who has covered HIV.
And the most important thing is prevention.
In the places designated for this purpose, "the distribution of condoms has actually increased; they used to be given out individually, now they give us packages of a hundred, which is good, but there are still people who do not have access to a condom", he said.
Young people are at risk of new infections.
"What do you need them for?" is a common mocking question from social workers, school counselors, pharmacy workers and health care workers who do not want to expose young people, the correspondent assured.
He proposed to reorient this inefficient distribution, with condoms not just being located behind the counter but in dispensers in public toilets in facilities frequented by young people.
Promiscuity is not to be promoted.
It is not to pay for the beer and the motel, as Governor Emilio González said when asked if condoms would be distributed under his administration.
"Sexuality is not like that; the best thing to do is to bring condoms closer to those who are already having sex", he said.
Key data from Jalisco
There are 13,435 cumulative cases (12,158 AIDS and 1,317 HIV).
The state ranks fourth nationally in new and cumulative AIDS cases, and 13th in HIV.
92% of cases are sexually transmitted, 6% are blood-borne and 2% perinatal.
It's estimated that 50,000 people are living with HIV because for every recorded case, there are four or five people who don't know it.
