Hector "Hetin" Reyes: "Basketball was my life"
World-renowned basketball player Hector "Hetin" Reyes has been involved in basketball for over 60 years and has traveled the world.
Few in Puerto Rico have such a vast intellectual collection of the history of the country's basketball as Hector "Hetin" Reyes.
Before being confined to a wheelchair by a stroke in 2008, Rexes spent six years in the sport, playing in the lower leagues, the first national league, representing and managing the BSN with the Vaqueros de Bayamón and as president of the Basketball Association.
"I've worn many hats in basketball my whole life, even several at once when I was president of the BSN, CEO of the national team and president of the federation in the 1990s", Reyes recalled when Primera Hora visited him at his home in Bayamón, where he lives with Isabel, his faithful wife of more than 50 years.
"Basketball was my life".
Reyes is not exaggerating.
The walls of his house are almost all decorated with photos and memories of his long career, and they testify to it.
Bayamón in the heart
The most emotional memories are those of his time with the Vaqueros from the mid-1950s as a player to 1982, when he celebrated his 15th anniversary as co-manager or CEO of the club.
"Those were my best years, the ones I enjoyed the most, because I was part of eight Vaqueros championships since 1967, whether as general manager, co-manager or coach.
It was a lot of fulfilling years, including five consecutive championships from 1971 to 1975.
And then I said goodbye to a championship in 1981, the year Jerome Mincy debuted on BSN.
From then on, Cuco took over from Ortiz, who was a very good manager", says Reyes.
I remember Gene Bartow, who was a coach here and who worked at the University of Alabama at Birmingham, saying to me, "I have a very strong, six-foot-tall player.
Do you want it?"
And that was the beginning of Mincy, one of the best players Puerto Rico has ever had.
Bartow then recommended free throw specialist Raymond Gausse, who was a naturalized citizen and one of our best pitchers.
I remember him saying that if Mincy had made a championship possible for Bayamon, Gausse would have made another.
The Vaqueros with Gausse championship was granted to him, but already from a distance, because he was already in the top position of the association in 1988.
At the time, he preferred to enjoy his and Mincy's executions on the national team.
I remember the first time we won the pre-Olympic tournament in Mexico against the United States.
Then came the 1990 World Cup, where we finished fourth, which should have been bronze, if it hadn't been for that Canadian referee who let us repeat the last move for the second time, Reyes said.
Was that group from the 1990 World Cup the best national team you ever saw?
She's one of the best, like the one that won the 2004 Olympics against the Dream Team.
But my favorite is the 1991 Pan American Games team in Cuba, where we won gold and gave the U.S. team a fight, like when they won bronze against us in the World Cup.
Not only Mincy, Gausse, Ramon Rivas, Fico López and "Piculín" (Ortiz) were back in that team, but also the young players (Javier) "Toñito" Colón and James Carter, the brothers León (Francisco and Edgar) and Mario "Quijote" Morales, who could not play in 1990 due to a knee injury.
One team that was perhaps not the best in terms of personalities, but with which we won a gold medal and which brought us great joy, was that of the pre-Olympic tournament in Neuquén, Argentina, in 1995.
With players like "Canito" Nieves, Pablo Alicea and the young Rolando Hourruiter as substitutes for the players suspended for the events at the Pan American Games in Mar del Plata, we won the gold medal against all odds.
Who was the best player in Puerto Rico?
That was without a doubt Piculín Ortiz.
His numbers at the international tournament level are impressive.
No one in Puerto Rico has dominated this level like Piculín.
And that's not counting his career in the different leagues he's played in.
Who was the best coach in Puerto Rico?
That's a difficult question to ask.
We had a number of good coaches like Julio Toro, Flor Meléndez, Carlos Morales, Raymond Dalmau, Armandito Torres.
Of the boys, I like Leo Arill's work.
What do you think is the best thing you've done in the league?
I was part of the most successful era of the national team from 1988 to 1995, which in the early 1990s included up to 17 teams in a season.
What else do you have to do?
There are things I would have introduced, such as the regionalisation of the lower categories.
Like the boys in Ponce, they only play in their territory and they only play in the national playoffs against teams from other parts of the island.
Today, children travel and play unnecessarily.
At least I see the result of the prescribed training and courses for coaches, officials and referees.
I'm proud of that.
What are you doing today?
I like to listen to music, watch YouTube videos of music from my time, enjoy my grandchildren, and occasionally go to a basketball game.
And of course, I enjoy the company of my wife, Isabel, who was always by my side.
