Beginning of the course studying the "End of the World"
Each week, students explore apocalyptic topics such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
Every semester, when the religion professor decided to teach a course on the end of the world, he knew he had an irresistible fishing hook: the end of the "long countdown" of the Mayan calendar on December 21, which many people believed meant the end of the world.
But Charmé had no idea what awaited him in the next two months: the devastating Hurricane Sandy, which some have dubbed "Deudarmageddon", and a growing conflict involving Israel, the place where Christian theorists believe the apocalypse begins.
"I didn't realize this was going to be the most apocalyptic semester ever", Charmé told students at Rutgers-Camden University in New Jersey this week.
If someone analyses what has happened in the world today as if we were thirty days away from it, this would be a really good period.
And he reminds us that bad is good for those with an apocalyptic mentality.
And he's not the only professor teaching courses on the "end of the world" this semester, which should be the last in history.
At Temple, Associate Professor Barry Vacker is teaching a course on media, culture and the end of the world.
Each week, students explore apocalyptic topics such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
"We are analysing why these ideas spread over time", he said, as well as the way hypothetical scenarios are offered that lead to a particular human behaviour.
If nuclear material falls into the hands of terrorists, for example, war could break out.
This month, students analyzed films with apocalyptic content and examined how they compare to real life.
"I tried to inform the students about what is possible, likely, credible and impossible", Vacker said.
On the main campus of the University of Pennsylvania, Latin American history professor Matthew Restall and his colleague Amara Solari, an assistant professor of art history and anthropology, have teamed up to offer a course simply titled "The End of the World".
"We are not recording 2012 so that we always have the option of resetting course in case the world doesn't end", said Restall.
Despite the "imminent doom", students must study, write projects and take final exams.
Penn State's final exam is held on the eve of the apocalypse, leaving students no choice but to "work until the night when the world supposedly ends", said Restall.
The courses were very popular.
"In two hours, there were no more seats", said Restall of his high-school class, which filled with 35 students.
For weeks before the semester started, we received e-mails from students asking if there were any seats available.
The students, for their part, assure us that the course is one of the most interesting.
"It's fascinating to see what people do to comfort themselves", said Bridgid Robinson, a 23-year-old Rutgers Camden student in religion and sociology from Haddonfield, New Jersey.
The apocalyptic sectarian or religious mentality is really just a matter of comfort or lack of it.
25-year-old psychology and nursing student Will Wekesa says he's seen all the apocalyptic movies.
"I have never heard of a class that teaches this", he said.
I'm enjoying it.
But none of the students interviewed - let alone a professor - declared that they believed in the December 21 deadline.
"Our first project was on the Mayan prophecy, and in a way we're discrediting it", said Julie Zeglen, a 21-year-old final year student at Temple from West Chester.
The Mayans never predicted the end of the world; it is just a key point in the calendar, Restall said.
He notes, however, that there is an apocalyptic fear in Western society that goes back several centuries when people reacted to changes in their environment by predicting the end of the world.
The Internet has fueled this speculation.
"Other places, people don't think that way", he says.
This is mainly the case in the English-speaking world.
Joseph Dougherty, a professor of religion at La Salle University who is teaching in the Philippines this year, quickly answers the question of whether he would take a course on "the end of the world".
"The Philippines is not part of the end of the world", he wrote, suggesting a higher court exception.
We have a pardon from the Pope.
Restall pointed out that over the years there was much talk of the Last Judgment, saying that if nothing happens on December 21, "people immediately think of a new date" or philosophize that December 21 is the beginning of a seven-year period after which the world will end.
Students and professors take this date lightly.
Several said they wanted to go to celebrations about "the end of the world".
